<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Calls for Direct Talks With Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official
Tuesday urged the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to resume
direct negotiations with Israel to discuss implementing the signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Israeli Foreign Ministry Eitan Bentsur
issued the call when he signed here an agreement with PNA chief
negotiator Saeb Erekat on extending the Temporary International
Presence in Hebron (TIPH) in the West Bank city Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Bentsur said that while the international community is helpful,
the two sides should develop "various channels for dialog at
different levels" to move forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We should not transfer our dialog and mutual contacts to
countries that are far away, nor to mediators, but we should
choose the path required by peace -- the path of direct
negotiations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the just-signed agreement, Israel and the PNA agreed to
extend the participation of Denmark, Italy, Norway, Sweden,
Switzerland and Turkey in TIPH operations for a period of three
months starting on August 1.
</P>
<P>
The task of the 122-member TIPH, established in January 1997
under the Hebron agreement, is promoting a feeling of security for
the Palestinians in Hebron, assisting the execution of projects
initiated by the donor countries and encouraging economic
development and growth in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Israel handed over 80 percent of Hebron to the PNA in January
last year, but it has retained control over the rest of the city
to protect 450 Jewish settlers living in the center.
</P>
<P>
Bentsur praised the TIPH for its role in helping "overcome the
rivalries (between the Israelis and the Palestinians) of the past
and the friction of the present."
</P>
<P>
Erekat, also PNA minister of local governments, urged Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to "respond to the American
initiative positively" to reach an agreement "bigger" than the one
he signed with Bentsur.
</P>
<P>
"We have no other choice but to exert every possible effort to
revive the peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has proposed that Israel withdraw from
another 13.1 percent of the West Bank in exchange for a tougher
PNA crackdown on terrorism. Despite the PNA's acceptance of the
plan, Israel has rejected it citing security reasons.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace process has been stalled since
March last year due to Israel's settlement expansion and delay in
carrying out the further troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
