<HEADLINE> Russia Opposes Chechnya Membership in U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Tuesday strongly opposed
Chechnya's entry into the United Nations, saying it merely a
member of the Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
Only states recognized internationally can claim membership in
the body, said Vladimir Rakhmanin, a spokesman for the Russian
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"Chechnya cannot be regarded as such state for it is an
integral part of Russia -- that is the stance of the Russian
Foreign Ministry" he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman's remark came in reaction to Chechen Foreign
Minister Movladi Udugov's announcement Monday on Chechnya's
intended application for U.N. membership.
</P>
<P>
Udugov said a package of documents had been compiled confirming
Chechnya as an independent state. The documents included the
Chechen Constitution and a peace treaty signed last May between
Russia and Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Chechnya won de facto independence from Moscow in the wake of
the 1994-1996 war, which officially ended with the signing of a
peace accord in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Kremlin wants Chechnya to stay within the Russian
Federation and only offers autonomous status for the volatile
region, while the Chechnya leadership insists that the region is
already an independent entity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
