<HEADLINE> Teen Girls Take Great Sex Risks in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Canadian teenagers are at greater
risk than ever in the past from unsafe sex, "The Globe and Mail"
newspaper on Tuesday quoted a panel as warning.
</P>
<P>
The Society of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, which was
holding its annual meeting in Victoria from Monday, announced that
the number of teenage pregnancies in Canada rose 18 percent from
1987 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
The upward trend is continuing, and as many as 50 percent of
teenage pregnancies are unintended, figures from the meeting
showed.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the number of abortions for young women between
15 and 19 is 50 percent higher than the increase among women aged
20 and older.
</P>
<P>
Teenage girls had the highest rates of sexually transmitted
diseases of any group, and the rate of chlamydia in the 15 to 19
age group was nine times the average among all women, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The panel recommended that parents should be just as involved
as teachers and doctors in teaching their children about sex and
contraception.
</P>
<P>
The panel requested that doctors make sexual health a central
part of basic health care, and the use of condoms be promoted for
all sexual encounters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
