<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GM1 Could Slow Parkinson's Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A naturally occurring substance
shows promise of slowing the progression of Parkinson's disease,
says a report by Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
Jay S. Schneider of the Jefferson Medical College of Thomas
Jefferson University in Philadelphia, and colleagues, tested an
experimental drug known as GM1 ganglioside on 45 patients with
Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
After 16 weeks of receiving the drug, those taking the
substance scored better in tests that measure stiffness and other
physical variables compared with patients who received a placebo.
Those who took the real drug said they were better able to perform
basic daily activities such as dressing themselves and handling
utensils.
</P>
<P>
The new drug is a normal part of the cell membrane that plays
an important role in cell growth, development and repair.
Parkinson's is caused by the death of cells in the brain that make
the chemical messenger dopamine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
