<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Spends Nearly 5.6 Million U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China's central government has
spent nearly 5.6 million U.S. dollars in the prevention and
control of HIV/AIDS in the past decade, said a Chinese official
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In 1987 the central government established a special fund for
HIV/AIDS prevention and control, vice health minister Yin Dakui
told the 12th World AIDS Conference being held in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The central government provided 1.3 million dollars for the
period 1987-1994, and another 4.28 million from 1995 to 1997,
according to Yin.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, all levels of government have been required
to include in their financial budgets the resourcing necessary to
implement HIV/AIDS prevention plans and to increase this financial
input if it is required as a result of changes in the epidemic
situation.
</P>
<P>
China has adopted the principle of government as the primary
provider of the resources, with financial burdens distributed
among different levels and funding from multiple sources, Yin
said.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the international community for its assistance in
the HIV/AIDS prevention work in China.
</P>
<P>
China has established cooperative relationships with
international organizations like the Joint United Nations Program
on HIV/AIDS, The U.N. Development Program, the U.N. Children's
Fund, the World Health Organization, the World Bank, the U.N. Fund
for Population Activities, the U.N. Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization, the European Union.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations resident coordinator in China
Arthur Holcome, the cumulative total support from international
organizations to China was 17.4 million dollars up to 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
