<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duisenberg: Euro Not Cure-All for European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, June 30 (Xinhua) -- President of the European
Central Bank (ECB), Wim Duisenberg, warned Tuesday that the single
European currency, the euro, is not a cure-all for economic
problems of many European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony in Frankfurt marking the founding of the
ECB, Duisenberg said the new central bank had a clear mandate of
maintaining price stability in the whole euro area which includes
11 EU countries that will adopt the euro in the first wave in
January next year.
</P>
<P>
"By fulfilling its mandate it will contribute to creating the
appropriate conditions for sustainable growth of incomes and
employment: the ultimate goals of economic policy," Duisenberg
said.
</P>
<P>
However, he also stressed that the monetary policy of the ECB
must be supported by sound fiscal and economic policies of
national governments of euro member states.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise, price stability can only be maintained at a high
cost in terms of lost income and employment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Similar view was also voiced by German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
in a speech to the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"It is without doubt that the euro is not a magic prescription
which can solve the problem of high unemployment in many European
countries overnight," Kohl said, adding that what were necessary
were to achieve more flexibility on the job markets and to conduct
more structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
"When everyone of us does his national homework, the euro will
open the great chance for new economic dynamic, sustainable growth
and secure jobs in the 21st century," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
As a historic project of the European integration, the euro is
to be launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The 11 EU countries to join the euro on that date are Austria,
Belgium, Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Portugal and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Denmark and Sweden have opted not to join the club in
the first wave while Greece has failed to meet the membership
criteria set by the EU Maastricht Treaty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
