<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. F-16 Fires Missile on Iraq Radar Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A United States F-16 fighter
fired a missile at an Iraqi surface-to-air missile battery in
southern Iraq early on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place at about 5:30 GMT near Basra in southern
Iraq. Coalition aircraft were conducting Operation Southern Watch,
the name given to the deny-flight mission which dates from the
aftermath of the 1991 Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi radar at the site had illuminated four British Tornados
patrolling the no-fly zone, signaling its intention to fire on the
jets, said Pentagon spokesman Col. Richard Bridges. That act
prompted the American response.
</P>
<P>
"Coalition aircraft pilots assigned to Joint Task
Force-Southwest Asia received cockpit indications that they were
being targeted by a missile site," said Navy Lt. John O'Neal,
spokesman for the U.S. Command, the joint military headquarters
responsible for the Persian Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
"This is considered an action requiring aggressive defensive
measures," he said.
</P>
<P>
The missile fired by the F-16, which accompanied the flight of
British Tornados, was a high-speed anti-radiation, or HARM missile.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, the coalition flights returned safely to their
bases in Saudi Arabia without further incident.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant O'Neal said he had no reports of any further hostile
activity by Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
