<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The New york Times
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton and his entourage came to China's
largest city Monday evening. To put his finger on the vibrant
pulse of modern China, his aides said, Mr. Clinton will spend two
days and three nights here talking to regular people.
</P>
<P>
-- Thousands of Serbian special police units and troops, backed
by artillery, tanks and other heavy armor, opened a series of
attacks against separatist rebel positions Monday morning. The
Serbs reported that an eight-year-old ethnic Albanian boy had been
killed and a man wounded. More than 8, 000 people were forced to
flee their homes in Belacevac and take refuge in nearby woods.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Washington and Baltimore will make an unprecedented joint
bid for the 2012 Olympic Games, organizers are set to announce
Tuesday, hoping to resolve a bitter behind-the-scenes battle over
the right to lead an effort that could bring billions of dollars
to the region.
</P>
<P>
-- The effort to reduce mother-to-child transmission of the
AIDS virus in poor African countries may be harder than people
think, and one of the main obstacles may be the pregnant women
themselves. Information presented at the 12th World AIDS
Conference Monday suggests that fear of rejection, and even of
physical harm, by family and neighbors may keep many women from
learning whether they are infected with the virus.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Two Midwestern banks are close to a merger that could be
valued at 5 billion or more dollars in stock, say people familiar
with the situation. A merger of Cincinnati's Star Banc and Firstar
of Milwaukee would create a company with about 625 branches in
eight states.
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's President Weizman urged early elections because of
a deadlock in peace talks with the Palestinians, but Prime
Minister Netanyahu dismissed the idea. Israel's President has no
authority to set elections, but his call could affect public
opinion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
