<HEADLINE> Dunga to Fight Tooth and Nail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian captain Carlos Dunga said he
was going to "fight tooth and nail" for his second World Cup triumph.
</P>
<P>
"I won't hesitate to do what I have to do so that everyone plays to
the best of his abilities," said Dunga.
</P>
<P>
"If all goes well, I have three more matches to play with Brazil...
I'm 34 years old and I've played for this team for eleven years,"
Dunga said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "I already won one World Cup in the United States in 1994,
but I'm disappointed not to have won Olympic gold."
</P>
<P>
Dunga said he dreamed of playing in the 2000 Olympics in Sydney,
but had to wait for a decision from the Olympic Committee regarding
players over 23.
</P>
<P>
He said if the Brazilians enter the final, goalkeeper Taffarel and
he will break the record for the number of games a Brazilian player
play in World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the record is held by Jairzinho at 16 games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
