<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Too Much to Expect From Indo-Pak Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 30 (Xinhua) -- How much should people expect
from next month's meeting between Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif and his Indian counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee on the
fringes of a SAARC summit in Colombo, capital of Sri Lanka?
</P>
<P>
Sharif and Vajpayee would be sitting together in Colombo in
late July at the 10th summit of the seven-nation South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC). Both Pakistan and
India have announced the two leaders would hold an important
bilateral meeting there.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first meeting between the two leaders after
India conducted five nuclear tests and Pakistan responded with six
of its own last month, causing increased tension between them and
in South Asia as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear tests have added heat to the unresolved Kashmir
dispute and the deep animosity and distrust between Pakistan and
India which had already fought three wars since their independence
some 50 years ago, putting the region under the threat of nuclear
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear tests, which have also put a strong global
nonproliferation regime at risk, have again highlighted the
immediate need for the two arch-rivals in South Asia to solve the
problems bedeviling their bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The international community, while condemning the shocking
actions by India and Pakistan, has been urging the two countries
to take urgent and effective steps to improve their strained ties
for the sake of a peaceful, stable and prosperous South Asia.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan's special envoy,
Alvaro de Soto, is currently visiting the region to consult with
countries concerned about the role of the U.N. in reducing the
tension between Pakistan and India. Annan has expressed his
readiness to mediate between the two countries and said that he
himself will visit the region "at right time."
</P>
<P>
Most recently, U.S. President Bill Clinton and Chinese
President Jiang Zemin, in their joint statement on South Asia
issued in Beijing on Saturday, reaffirmed their countries'
commitment to prevent a nuclear and missile race in the region and
to "assist, where possible, India and Pakistan to resolve
peacefully the difficult and long-standing differences between
them, including the issue of Kashmir."
</P>
<P>
They also welcomed the resumption of dialogue between the two
countries and encouraged them to continue such dialogue, saying:
"We stand ready to assist in the implementation of
confidence-building measures between them and encourage the
consideration of additional measures of this type."
</P>
<P>
Against this backdrop, next-month's encounter between Sharif
and Vajpayee has assumed a particular dimension as people are
pinning high hopes on the meeting to revitalize the foreign
secretary-level talks between Pakistan and India, which broke down
last September in New Delhi. The foreign secretary-level talks
have been considered essential for the improvement of the
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
However, some observers have cautioned people against expecting
too much from the forthcoming Sharif-Vajpayee meeting, as neither
Pakistan nor India has shown any significant change in their
positions on reopening the foreign secretary-level talks and the
Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Kashmir, whose sovereignty was left unresolved when India and
Pakistan became independent in 1947, is seen as the core
impediment in improving their ties.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan insists that the talks be resumed with an active
international engagement, on the basis of the agreement reached
here by the two sides last June under which eight issues including
peace and security and Kashmir would be discussed in future talks.
</P>
<P>
But India refuses any third-party intervention, and demands the
talks be held just on a bilateral basis and in light of proposals
it made to Pakistan in January which Pakistan has rejected as
"unrealistic and unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
India has refused to receive U.N. envoy De Soto, and rejected
Japan's offer to host a Pakistani-Indian meeting on Kashmir in
Tokyo and the Sino-U.S. joint statement on South Asia while
Pakistan has welcomed all these international initiatives.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan Sunday said De
Soto's visit represented "a first step towards an effective and
sustained engagement by the United Nations on the issue of peace
and security in South Asia."
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after his meeting with De Soto Sunday
evening, Gohar said: "We hope that the Colombo meeting (between
Sharif and Vajpayee) would make some progress to resolve the core
issue of Kashmir," he said. "I don't have much hope... there will
be more or less the same in the meeting."
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said that although it would be unrealistic to
expect some breakthrough in the Sharif-Vajpayee meeting, people
still hope it would generate some momentum and hope, or at least
some confidence-building measures, for the acceleration of the
reconciliation process between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India have been on bad terms with each other for a
long time and both have been spending billions of dollars on their
defenses to keep themselves ready for wars.
</P>
<P>
In its 1998-1999 fiscal budget, India has increased its
military spending by 14 percent to the tune of 10 billion U.S.
dollars, and Pakistan has increased its defense outlay by 8.4
percent to about 3.3 billion dollars despite their serious
financial difficulties compounded by economic sanctions imposed by
the West for their nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
In this game of numbers and arms race, the losers are only
their already fragile economies, analysts said, adding that the
Pakistani-Indian animosity has also dented the hope of achieving
any meaningful economic cooperation among the SAARC countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
