<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Parliament Approves Budget for New Fiscal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's parliament on Tuesday
approved the budget for the 1998-99 fiscal year beginning July 1
through the passage of the appropriation bill.
</P>
<P>
The bill authorizes the government to withdraw a total amount
of 404.53 billion taka (about 8.79 billion U.S. dollars) from the
consolidate fund to meet its expenditure during the next fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the parliament passed 92 demands for grant by voice
vote, and rejected all the cut motions by the opposition members
of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The budget was passed following the approval on Monday of the
Finance Bill 1998, to come into effect on July 1, after Finance
Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria withdrew or reduced taxes, duties and
value-added taxes on 16 items.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of the proposals for enhanced taxes and duties
were based on the discussion on the budget by the opposition
members of parliament, suggestions offered by different business
bodies and comments made in newspapers, the finance minister told
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Withdrawal or reduction of the new taxation proposals would
cause a revenue loss of over 277 million taka (about 6 million
U.S. dollars), and the government would make good the loss by
initiating appropriate administrative measures, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
