<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Hails U.N. Resolutions on Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus applauded Tuesday the
United Nations Security Council for adopting two resolutions on
renewing the U.N. peacekeeping mission in the divided island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing here, government spokesman
Chirstos Stylianides said Cyprus is satisfied with the two
resolutions which "confirm the framework and the principles which
should govern a Cyprus solution and the basis of intercommunal
talks."
</P>
<P>
The resolutions 1178 and 1179 were unanimously passed by the
Security Council on Monday. They renewed the mandate of the
U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) until December 31,
1998, and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's mission of good
offices in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the resolutions are very important because
they are "clear reference to a single sovereignty and
international personality and a single citizenship."
</P>
<P>
He termed the resolutions as a U.N. reply "to the efforts by
Turkey and (Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf) Denktash to undermine the
status of the Republic of Cyprus and upgrade the self-styled
Turkish Cypriot regime."
</P>
<P>
But Stylianides expressed regret that the Security Council
refrained from blaming the Turkish side "more clearly" for its
intransigence and the lack of progress in Cyprus peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Since last July, Denktash has refused to resume the
negotiations with the Greek Cypriot leader Glafcos Clerides
unless his breakaway entity in northern Cyprus is recognized and
the Cypriot government suspends its accession talks with the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in
1974 following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", which was recognized only
by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The UNFICYP was deployed in 1964, four years after Cyprus
gained independence from Britain, when inter-communal clashes
broke out between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities.
</P>
<P>
The 1,200-strong UNFICYP troops have been patrolling along the
180-kilometer-long buffer zone separating the Turkish troops
stationed in the north from the Greek Cypriot National Guards in
the south.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying to reunite the divided island as a
bizonal and bicommunal federation through peace talks, but so far
no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
