<HEADLINE> 10 Kurdish Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Ten members of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) were killed Tuesday in a clash with the
Turkish security forces in the southeast of the country, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said that a group of PKK militants opened fire
at guards of Bagisli village in Hakkari province late Monday
night, leaving three of them dead and three others wounded.
</P>
<P>
After the clash, the Turkish security forces rushed to the
village and fought against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's National Security Council Monday decided to extend the
state of emergency for another four months starting from July 30
in the eastern and southeastern provinces, where the PKK rebels
often launch attacks on military and civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a war since 1984 in an attempt to
establish an independent Kurdish state in the southeast. More than
35,000 people have been killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
