<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Lifts Ban on Fresh Fish Imports from Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Union lift ban on
fresh fish imports from Kenya beginning from Wednesday, head of
EU regional delegation Luc Saltzman announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Kenyans can export fish to the European community starting
tomorrow (July 1). The remaining health and sanitary problems
will continue being reviewed and the final decision will be made
in January next year," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission banned the imports of fresh fish from
Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania and Mozambique in January this year on
the account of a possible contamination with cholera.
</P>
<P>
The ban does not affect frozen fish which are subject to
"systematic six-day laboratory testing," according to the EU
office here.
</P>
<P>
It's not known so far if the EU has lift the similar ban on
the other three African countries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, EU's Permanent Veterinary Committee recommended the
ban be lifted as early as July 1.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's fishing industry is based at Kisumu on Lake Victoria
and at the coast. With water hyacinth already clogging up
Kisumu's port, the EU ban dealt a major blow to the area's
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
Official data show that in 1996, Kenya exported 12 million
kilograms of fresh and frozen fish valued at 18.7 billion
Shillings (315 million U.S. Dollars) to EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands was the largest market, taking 843 million
Shillings (14.1 million Dollars), with France, Germany and Italy
next in line.
</P>
<P>
The problem started last year when a bacterium called
salmonella was detected in some imported Lake Victoria Nile Perch
in Spain and Italy. EU then tightened its checks on imported fish
from this region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: SAARC Countries Make Progress in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Great progress has been made in
the field of agriculture in the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) region on account of cooperation
among the member countries, a SAARC official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Liaquat Ali Choudhury, director at the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Secretariat, said SAARC has two technical committees separately on
agriculture and rural development through which it formulates and
undertakes programs.
</P>
<P>
In the field of agriculture, a priority area of cooperation
among the member countries which are basically agricultural
countries, the emphasis has been placed on production of food
grains, cash crops, livestock and fishery as well as preservation
of natural resources such as land and water which are vital for
the sector, he told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said great progress has been made in the field with food
production having been increased manifold.
</P>
<P>
Though some member countries are still not self-sufficient in
food due to overpopulation, the SAARC countries have avoided any
major famine. "This is really a great achievement for all the
SAARC countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian Food Security Reserve, which serves as a
cushion against food shortage in the region, became operational in
1988. Though no major food crisis has hit the region since then,
all the member countries have food reserves at specific locations,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The director noted that there are still scopes for boosting
agricultural production, so nowadays the emphasis is being placed
on development of indigenous technologies and their wide
dissemination.
</P>
<P>
He said that in its meeting held last October in New Delhi, the
technical committee on agriculture conducted a major thematic
discussion on agricultural perspective for South Asia to the year
2020.
</P>
<P>
The meeting underscored the need for realization of the full
potential of science and technology for sustained growth in
agricultural production in the region.
</P>
<P>
It also highlighted the importance of promoting intra-regional
cooperation to raise productivity in the member countries to the
world level.
</P>
<P>
In September in Dhaka, Bangladesh, there will be a workshop on
transfer of technology, to be organized by the SAARC Agricultural
Information Center, he said. The workshop, the first of its kind
in the region, will focus on replicable technologies in the region
and new and frontier technologies on agriculture in the world.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC region is one of the poorest in the world and the
majority of its 1.2 billion population live in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
On rural development, the concerned technical committee has
accorded priorities on how to eradicate poverty from the rural
areas of member countries, how to generate employment in the most
cost-effective manner and how to best develop the rural
infrastructure, Director Choudhury said.
</P>
<P>
"Recently, more and more emphasis is being placed on making
rural credit available on a wide scale to the rural poor," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the member countries also cooperate in providing
housing and skill-oriented training to them.
</P>
<P>
Under the SAARC youth and volunteers scheme, youth and
volunteers are brought together in a member country where there
are successful programs. In this way, they can help member
countries share the experience and draw the lessons, he said.
</P>
<P>
While great progress has been made, only 10 to 20 percent of
the huge potential has been tapped by member countries for
cooperation in agriculture and rural development, he said.
</P>
<P>
"SAARC is only now beginning to realize the potential of
regional cooperation," he explained. "Since the SAARC
institutional structure is still not that elaborate, we could not
achieve what we should have. But I think gradually, if we can put
our efforts together, we can achieve much more."
</P>
<P>
SAARC was formed in December 1985 to promote economic and trade
cooperation among its seven member countries -- Bangladesh,
Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
