<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Home Price Rises Slow As Mortgage Lending Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- House prices in Britain rose by an
average of 11.3 percent in the year to June, down from an annual
rate of increase of 11.9 percent in May, Nationwide, Britain's
largest building society said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of property transactions in May totalled just
108,000, the lowest figure in nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
David Parry, Nationwide's divisional director of planning,
said: "Supply shortages are still dogging the market, with estate
agents recording very low levels of stock."
</P>
<P>
Some analysts fear that, with the Bank of England considering
further interest rate rises and unemployment likely to rise later
this year, the market could even go into reverse.
</P>
<P>
Separate figures published by the Bank reveal that much of the
activity in the mortgage market is a result of existing homeowners
taking advantage of some competitive deals to remortgate their
homes.
</P>
<P>
Net mortgage lending fell sharply from 2.3 billion pounds (3.68
billion U.S. dollars) in April to 1.8 billion (2.88 billion U.S.
dollars) in May and now stands below the level recorded at the
same point last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
