<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Local Election Proceeds Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Cars and trucks shuttled along the
March 8th Center, the major street of the Mozambican capital
Maputo, and a few youngsters bask in the sun along the street,
while businessmen were bustling in the free market Tuesday when
local elections were being held nationwide.
</P>
<P>
A woman official working at Coop polling station said that
everything seemed to have gone normally except for the unexpected
low turn-out rate, which was estimated at about 60 to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Joaquim Chissano, Chairman of the ruling Mozambican Liberation
Front (Frelimo), said after casting vote at Josina Machel
station, that there should not and could not be any turmoil for
the election.
</P>
<P>
Chissano said that the government had done a lot, including
the education of voters and the preparation against violence, for
the election.
</P>
<P>
On the opposition Mozambican National Resistance Movement
(Renamo)'s campaign against voting for the election, Chissano
said that Remano has the legal right to do so, as long as it is
doing this in a peaceful way.
</P>
<P>
Renamo's Chairman, Afonao Dhlakama, said Sunday that his
organization would not have any demonstration against the
elections.
</P>
<P>
Remano and 16 other parties had announced to boycot the local
elections on the account of the mal-practice occurred during the
voters-registration last year.
</P>
<P>
No news is yet available from other cities about the election.
</P>
</TEXT>
