<HEADLINE> Cohen: Missile Attack Serves as Warning to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said on Tuesday the United States was firing a missile on
Iraq's radar site to warn Baghdad that it should not intervene
with U.S. and its allies' patrol mission over the no-fly zone in
southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Cohen was commenting on the missile attack by a U.S. F-16
fighter at an Iraqi surface-to-air missile battery in southern
Iraq early on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It certainly was a signal that we sent that our forces are
going to fly the no-fly zone," he spoke to a Reuters TV
interview after attending a seminar with other NATO defense
ministers.
</P>
<P>
"We're hoping that the situation won't escalate," he added.
</P>
<P>
A Pentagon spokesman said the F-16 fired a high-speed
anti-radiation missile at the Iraqi missile battery because the
Iraqi radar at the battery site locked onto four British
Tornadoes conducting patrol mission over the no-fly zone in
southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place at about 5:30 GMT near the city of
Basra in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Central Command based in Tampa, Florida, which overseas
U.S. operations in the Gulf said pilots received cockpit
indications that "they were being targeted by a missile site."
</P>
<P>
"This is considered an action requiring aggressive defensive
measures," a spokesman for the Central Command said.
</P>
<P>
The F-16 was accompanied by a flight of British Tornados when
it fired the missile at the Iraqi radar site. Afterwards, they
returned safely to their bases in Saudi Arabia without further
incident.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Central Command plans to order an immediate resumption
of the patrols. 
</P>
</TEXT>
