<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams U.S. Missile Attack on Missile Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Tuesday slammed missile
attack by the United States on a missile site in the southern
province of Basra, saying "it is an aggressive and unjustifiable
action."
</P>
<P>
"It is another proof of aggressiveness of the Americans, and it
is a clear evidence of their aggressiveness of the security and
sovereignty of the Iraqi people," the spokesman of the Iraqi
Ministry of Information and Culture said.
</P>
<P>
An American F-16 fighter fired an anti-radiation missile at
around 0530GMT at an Iraqi surface-to-air missile battery.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British officials said that an Iraqi radar at the
missile site illuminated four British patrol planes, prompting the
American response.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman denied the allegation, saying "no radar has
been opened at all."
</P>
<P>
"It might be a step toward planning a new all-out aggression
against Iraq by preparing the grounds for such acts," he added.
</P>
<P>
The missile fell 18 kilometers from the nearest radar, the
spokesman said, adding that it hit some water tanks that are 12
kilometers north of Um-Khasir City in Basra Province.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. F-16 fighter which fired the missile was accompanying
a flight of British planes enforcing the no-fly zone in southern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
British officials have reportedly said that no further action
is planned, and that the allied flights over the southern no-fly
zone resumed normal flights.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zone was imposed by U.S., British and French forces
in 1991 with a claimed aim of protecting Shiite Muslim Iraqis from
alleged government oppression. An extension of the zone in 1996
reaches the 33rd parallel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
