<HEADLINE> Iranian Students Call for Dissolution of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Angered by the Majlis' (parliament)
dismissal of former interior minister, thousands of Iranian
pro-moderate students Tuesday called for dissolution of the
conservative Majlis.
</P>
<P>
"Majlis, Dissolve Majlis, Dissolve," the students shouted at a
rally in support of the dismissed Abdollah Nouri at the technical
faculty of Tehran University, which was arranged by a pro-moderate
students' group Unity Consolidation Office (UCO).
</P>
<P>
Holding pictures of President Mohammad Khatami, the students
also chanted "Khatami, Khatami, we support you," and "Students
Aware, Impeachment (against Nouri) Unjust."
</P>
<P>
Although Nouri and Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance
Ataollah Mohajerani strongly called on the students not to shout
radical slogans, the exciting participants condemned the
conservatives for making troubles for the government.
</P>
<P>
At the gathering, speakers lashed out at the conservatives for
their efforts to weaken Khatami's government, including the
inflicting of "serious damages to the Islamic system and the
country" through ousting Nouri.
</P>
<P>
Nouri was sacked on June 21 by the conservative Majlis with
a censure motion, despite the fact that Khatami threw all his
weight behind Nouri. In a swift reaction, Khatami appointed Nouri
as vice president for development and social affairs.
</P>
<P>
A student leader said at the gathering that Nouri's dismissal
was predefined because it happened at a time "when the Iranian
people are attracted by world cup football matches and the
students are busy for examinations."
</P>
<P>
He criticized the conservative Majlis deputies for their
decision against the people's will, saying that any move against
the people's will would be detrimental to the country and the
Islamic system.
</P>
<P>
The students reiterated their support for the government of
Khatami, calling for reforms in some of the country's state
institutions, such as radio and television, the judiciary and the
police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
