<HEADLINE> Greece Welcomes U.N. Resolutions on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Greece Tuesday hailed the U.N.
resolutions on the Cyprus problem as "positive".
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Undersecretary Yiannos Kranidiotis said that the
resolutions passed Monday by the U.N. Security Council on the
Cyprus problem indirectly attributed responsibility for the
breakdown in talks between the Greek-Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot
communities of the island with the Turkish-Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the Security Council's insistence that any
settlement of the Cyprus problem should be based on the creation
of one state with single sovereignty, a single international
entity and single citizenship.
</P>
<P>
He said it was particularly positive that the resolutions came
at a time when Turkey was trying to reset its objectives with
respect to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Turkey must now realize that the international community was
not willing to discuss any solution other than one based on a
bizonal, bicommunal federation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an abortive
coup-backed by Athens. 
</P>
