<HEADLINE> Turkey Extends Northern Iraq Monitoring Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Parliament on Tuesday
voted to extend the mission on monitoring northern Iraq, known as
Northern Watch, for another six months.
</P>
<P>
"The government's request has been accepted," Deputy Speaker
Kamer Genc told the semi-official Anatolia News Agency following
the parliamentary voting.
</P>
<P>
The proposal for extending the monitoring mission was presented
to the parliament by Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, who said
that the mission is still of significance to Turkey's
"territorial integrity".
</P>
<P>
Iraq lost its effective control of northern Iraq following the
1991 Gulf War, and some warring factions have been fighting for
dominance over the region since then.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Watch mission, launched in January 1997 as a
replacement of the Operation Provide Comfort, has been carried out
by Turkish, British and American warplanes deployed in the
Incirlik Air Base near the southern city of Adana. 
</P>
