<HEADLINE> Gore Says US to Respond "Decisively" to Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
said on Tuesday that the United States would respond decisively to
any hostile acts by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to patrol the no-fly zone to reduce the
threat that Saddam Hussein poses to the region and we will
continue to respond decisively to any hostile acts that threaten
the lives of our pilots," Gore told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Gore made the comment after a U.S. F-16 fighter fired a
missile at an Iraqi radar site near Basra in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred at 5:30 when pilots of four British
Tornadoes patrolling the no-fly zone in southern Iraq received
cockpit indications that they were targeted by a the Iraqi radar
at a surface-to-air missile battery near Basra. The F-16,
accompanying the flight of the tornadoes immediately responded
with firing a high-speed anti-radiation missile at the radar
site.
</P>
<P>
Gore said Washington did not know whether the incident in
which Iraqi radar "locked on" to the British aircraft was a
deliberate provocation and he urged people not to jump to
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know for certain but I would urge you not to assume
that it's a deliberate provocation. We don't know for certain,"
he told reporters. "But we do know from the history of
patrolling the no-fly zone that there are a lot of incidents
like this from time to time and there are other possible
explanations."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iraq condemned the U.S. firing of the missile,
saying it was "an aggressive and unjustifiable action."
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi official said the U.S. missile that was fired landed
at a distance of 18 km from the nearest Iraqi radar.
</P>
<P>
He said the missile attack "might be a step toward planning
for a new all-out aggression against Iraq." 
</P>
</TEXT>
