<HEADLINE> U.S. Businessman Deported From S. Leone for Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. businessman, Roger Crooks,
has been deported from Sierra Leone for alleged link with arms
trafficking involving Northern Ireland guerrillas, media reports
reaching here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
James Kakanyako, a police commissioner, was quoted as saying
in Freetown Monday that last Sunday Crooks was put on a plane
which left the Sierra Leonean capital Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Crooks was given 48 hours to pack his baggage, and yesterday
afternoon was escorted to Lungi airport into the plane that took
him out of the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
The police commissioner declined to give any more details of
the alleged arms deal, but he said that "Crooks was deported for
trafficking in arms from Northern Ireland to Sierra Leone and the
other way around."
</P>
<P>
A report, however, quoted senior aides to President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah as saying that Crooks was expelled in connection
with plans to supply arms to the military junta that toppled
Kabbah in a coup last May but was flushed out in February this
year.
</P>
<P>
Crooks was said to be an influential figure in Sierra Leone,
where he had a wide range of business, including operating the
country's top hotel, the Mammy Yoko Hotel.
</P>
<P>
Since Kabbah's resuming office in March, about 23 businessmen,
mainly Lebanese, have been deported for alleged links with the
toppled military junta, a report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
