<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Ousted Minister Vows to Fight for Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Iran's ousted Interior Minister
Abdollah Nouri Tuesday vowed to continue his fight for public
freedom.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a pro-moderate student gathering at Tehran
University, Nouri said the religion of Islam is for freedom and
democracy which are legitimate rights of the people under the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
"I am surprised why some people who are afraid that the
constitution is implemented, and the freedom and democracy defined
by the constitution are given to the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nouri, a firm supporter of the moderate President Mohammad
Khatami, was impeached by the conservative-dominated Majlis
(Parliament) on June 21 in a vote of no-confidence. He was later
appointed Vice President for Development and Social Affairs by
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Since Khatami, an advocate for social reforms and freedom, was
elected president in May last year, the rift between the moderates
and conservatives has been deepened.
</P>
<P>
Nouri stressed that the heaviest blow to Islam is depicting it
as a religion of strangulation and tyranny.
</P>
<P>
His speech was frequently interrupted by students' slogans in
support of him and Khatami.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Nouri lashed out at the conservatives for limiting
the power of Khatami, saying that "they fight his programs with
ever more strength and determination."
</P>
<P>
During a farewell ceremony at the Interior Ministry, Nouri said
that he is more concerned about the future of Khatami because the
conservatives want to "throw a spoke into the wheels of the
executive."
</P>
<P>
He called on the people to show support for the president.
"Khatami is a victim of injustice, so the people must be
vigilant," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
