<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Changes Not to Affect Economy: Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz Tuesday said that country's economic programs will not be
affected by the changes in the government as some people fear for.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here noted that Yilmaz made the statement to assure
the public that the early elections scheduled for April 1999 will
not bring about a negative impact on these economic plans.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in the parliament building here,
Yilmaz urged the parliament to adopt laws to help make the
economic programs successful.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has worked out a series of plans
concerning balance of payments, the inflation rate and budget
targets for 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
The economic programs were encouraged by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) which signed a cooperation agreement with
Turkish State Minister for economic issues Gunes Taner in
Washington last week.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz said the agreement shows that the IMF is assuring the
international financial markets as to the credibility of Turkey's
current economic programs.
</P>
<P>
"The signal which the IMF will send to international markets
concerning the realism and reliability of our economic program and
our government's determination to implement this program is
expected to affect the Turkish economy very positively," the
Turkish prime minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
