<HEADLINE> Kenya to Commercialize Public Water Utilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Minister for Water Sources
Kipng'eno arap Ng'eny announced Tuesday that the government has
decided to commercialize the country's public water utilities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called for enhanced participation of private
sectors in water management and development across Africa.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the opening ceremony of the Water
Africa '98 Conference and Exhibition which is set to end
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The conference theme is "Towards the Millennium: Strategies
for Drought, Pollution and Population Pressures."
</P>
<P>
Experts and companies from Europe, North America, Middle East
and more than 10 African countries attended the biggest annual
event across the continent in this field.
</P>
<P>
Among those displayed at the show are products and services
for water supply, treatment, distribution and storage, waste
water treatment and disposal, groundwater exploration and
development.
</P>
<P>
Water Africa '98 is the sixth annual event in a series which
began in Johannesburg, South Africa, in 1993 and last year's show
was held in Harare, Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
