<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Says No Plan to Boost U.S. Forces in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen
said Tuesday that the United States has no plan to bolster the
20,000 U.S. forces in the Gulf region following an incident in
which a U.S. F-16 firing fired a missile at an Iraqi radar site.
</P>
<P>
"This will not alter our plans" to continue drawing down U.S.
forces in the region, he told reporters at the Pentagon. "I don't
think we should draw any conclusion from this particular one
incident."
</P>
<P>
Cohen made the remarks after the F-16 fighter fired a
high-speed anti-radiation missile at an Iraqi radar site that was
said to have illuminated four British Tornado warplanes patrolling
the no-fly zone in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said he decided not to make any move to reinforce the
U.S. military presence because the incident "might be a situation
of an isolated example."
</P>
<P>
"We have not seen any evidence from the Iraqis altering their
air defense system. We have not seen any examples of higher alert.
We have not seen them moving their radars and tracking systems
around in any sort of aggressive fashion," he said. "So it might
be a situation of an isolated example."
</P>
<P>
But Cohen warned Baghdad that Washington would make vigorous
response to any Iraqi acts that constitute a threat to U.S. and
its allies' aircraft conducting patrol missions over the no-fly
zone.
</P>
<P>
"If our aircraft, or those of our allies, are threatened, it
will be met with a very vigorous response," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vice President Al Gore told reporters in the
Roosevelt Room of the White House that the United States would
take "decisive" action to respond to any "hostile acts" by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to patrol the no-fly zone to reduce the
threat that Saddam Hussein poses to the region and we will
continue to respond decisively to any hostile acts that threaten
the lives of our pilots," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gore, however, urged people not to jump to conclusions about
the incident whether it was a deliberate provocation by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I would urge you not to assume that it's a deliberate
provocation," he told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
