<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Prime Minister Visits Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi arrived here Tuesday night, leading Italy as the pioneer of
the European countries in improving relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's visit to Tehran is the first one by a western head of
government since the Islamic revolution in 1979. Both Tehran and
Rome see the visit as an important step for expansion of
Tehran-Rome relations and a further detente between Iran and the
European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Prodi said that he has brought a message from
the EU countries to the Iranian government, Tehran radio reported,
adding that Iran plays an important role in the region and the
world.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said Italy and Iran have enjoyed friendly relations for
long and they can further expand their bilateral relations in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Prodi will hold talks with Iranian President Mohammad Khatami,
First Vice President Hassan Habibi, Chairman of the State
Expediency Council and former President Hashemi Rafsanjani and
other senior Iranian officials.
</P>
<P>
The talks are expected to focus mainly on Iran's ties with the
EU, the Middle East peace process, terrorism and weapons of mass
destruction. But Iranian officials said that the main agenda of
Prodi's visit was to strengthen bilateral relations in political,
economic, cultural and parliamentary areas.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's trip came four months after the ground-breaking visit
by Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini who called on the west
to support Khatami's moderate government.
</P>
<P>
Dini came to Tehran, days after the EU lifted the ban on
ministerial contact with Tehran following the more than one year
freeze on the EU's "critical dialog" with Iran in a protest to
Iran's alleged support for terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Italy was Iran's biggest trade partner in 1997 with a trade
volume at 2.3 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
