<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Announces to Cut Oil Output as of Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced on Tuesday to
decrease oil output as of Wednesday by 10 percent in accordance
with the recent decision by the Organization of the Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) with an aim to boost oil price.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, Director
of international affairs of the National Iranian Oil Company
(NIOC) Hojjatollah Ghanimifard made the announcement without
mentioning Iran's current oil production and the amount to be cut
down.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar Zanganeh said earlier that
Iran would reduce its production by 305,000 barrels per day (bpd)
according to OPEC decision. Some reports said that Iran's current
oil production is around 3.6 million bpd though its OPEC-set quota
was raised to 3.942 million bpd in November.
</P>
<P>
Ghanimifard said that the decision for lowering oil output is
based on the concept of bolstering the international oil market.
</P>
<P>
On June 24, OPEC members agreed to further reduce their
outputs by 1.355 million bpd, after oil market showed no sign of
recovery despite of OPEC's cuts in March.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh strongly urged the OPEC members to respect the
commitments to output cuts, saying that "respect of the recent
OPEC decision will be the most effective element for lifting oil
price soon."
</P>
<P>
However, many oil experts doubt if all the OPEC members would
stick to their promises. Oil price is still declining in recent
days as the world market showed no positive reaction to the OPEC
decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
