<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Hopes for Closer Sino-U.S. Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton said today that he will work for a closer partnership and
deeper friendship between China and the U.S. and a better life for
the people of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Clinton expressed this hope today while touring this largest
metropolis in China, the third leg of his nine-day, five-city
state visit to China.
</P>
<P>
During today's breakfast, the U.S. president told more than 500
American and Chinese entrepreneurs that China is one of the major
trading partners of the United States, bringing about more job
opportunities to the U.S. and helping prosper its economy.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that the success of China is related
to not only its own development, but also to the prosperity and
stability of the U.S. and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
At noon, Clinton visited the Shanghai Stock Exchange (SSE) in
the company of Shanghai Mayor Xu Kuangdi.
</P>
<P>
SSE General manager Tu Guangshao briefed Clinton and other
American visitors on the Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Situated in the Pudong New Area of Shanghai, the 4,000-sq.m.
SSE, the first of its kind in China which was set up in December
of 1990, now handles A-share, B-share, funds, treasury bonds,
enterprise bonds and financial bonds, among others.
</P>
<P>
At the end of May this year, 407 enterprises were listed on the
Exchange and 446 kinds of stocks with their combined market
capitalization reaching 1.1867 trillion yuan (about 143 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
On behalf of more than 1,000 traders at the exchange, Chen
Chen, a trader with China's largest securities company,"Shenyin
International", presented President Clinton with a red vest
printed with the year "1998" as a souvenir.
</P>
<P>
While he was showing around the crowd of busy traders wearing
red vests, the majority of them being young people, the U.S.
president inquired about the trading. Many of them responded in
fluent English.
</P>
<P>
Clinton praised many of the traders as young and energetic. He
told SSE General Manager Tu Guangshao that "you should feel proud
of the success of the stock exchange."
</P>
<P>
About 3:00 p.m., President Clinton and other American officials
accompanying him toured a neighborhood in the western part of
Shanghai, where they were greeted by some 400 residents.
"ongradulations! Congradulations!" Clinton said to them upon
learning that they all have their own housing now. The U.S.
president also called on a resident Yu Jianyuan and his family.
</P>
<P>
Yu is just one of those in Shanghai who have benefited from a
housing reform the city launched in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai was one of the pilot cities in China to carry out the
housing reform aimed at ending the traditional welfare housing
distribution and alleviating the housing shortage. Up to now,
one-third of its households have bought their own housing with
mortgage loans, or by way of paying the cost in instalments or
with housing accumulation funds.
</P>
<P>
At noon today. the U.S. president had his luncheon with 12
local private business people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
