<HEADLINE> New Philippine Government to Shun Borrowings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
Wednesday said his administration will concentrate on improving
the government's finances and will resort to borrowing only when
"absolutely necessary."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with newsmen, the new president said it had
been his policy even when he was still mayor of San Juan not to
borrow and "it will continue to be my policy now that I am
president."
</P>
<P>
Estrada called for belt-tightening in his inaugural speech
Tuesday in view of the current economic difficulties as evidenced
by the fact that the national government has incurred a 38 billion
peso (about 1 billion U.S. dollars) budgetary deficit.
</P>
<P>
In his directive to the new cabinet Tuesday, the president
asked them to review the remaining budget for 1998 and identify
areas for further savings.
</P>
<P>
He also asked them to review the proposed budget for 1999 of
their respective departments, including all the agencies and
government-owned corporations attached to their departments, and
to ensure that all expenses are consistent with the policies and
projects of the administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
