<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Macao Can Learn From Hong Kong Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Macao can learn a lot from the
successful implementation of the "one country, two systems" policy
in Hong Kong in the past year, local newspapers and celebrities
said.
</P>
<P>
A commentary in Wednesday's Macao Daily News said that on the
first anniversary of Hong Kong's return to China, residents in
Hong Kong and Macao can see for themselves that the Chinese
Central Government is firm in carrying out the policy of "one
country, two systems' and "Hong Kong people administering Hong
Kong."
</P>
<P>
The Central Government has done nothing to interfere with the
running of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) and
instead has done its utmost to support Hong Kong in maintaining
its financial stability.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Hong Kong SAR Government has taken appropriate
measures to stimulate the economic growth after it was confronted
with unexpected difficulties in the wake of the Asian financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's economy will gradually revive in two to three
years," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Correio Sino-Macanese Daily said in a commentary Wednesday
that the experience over the past year in Hong Kong since its
handover has proved that the policy of "one country, two systems"
is "correct, scientific, and practical."
</P>
<P>
The commentary described the first year of the HKSAR as a total
success
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has fully exercised its rights of administration,
legislation and independent jurisdiction, and the freedom
protected by the Hong Kong Basic Law has been fully guaranteed and
respected, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
In particular, Hong Kong and its residents can feel the dignity
and pride which they could not enjoy before its return to the
motherland, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leaders of some grass-roots organizations in Macao
said the success in Hong Kong has boosted the confidence of Macao
</P>
<P>
Vitor Ng, president of the Macao Exporters and Importers
Association, said Macao can learn a lot from the successful
experience in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said Macao residents' confidence in the policy of "one
country, two systems" has been boosted by the fact that it has
worked well in Hong Kong, and that the Central Government has
never tried to intervene in Hong Kong's affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Announces Infrastructure Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Wednesday announced
the establishment of an Infrastructure Development Fund to help
revive infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar
Ibrahim told a press conference that the fund with an initial size
of 5 billion ringgit (about 1.25 billion U.S. dollars) would help
revive infrastructure projects which had been deferred or
abandoned but were deemed to be critical and should be revived
immediately.
</P>
<P>
He said the fund would also help projects already in progress
so that they could be speeded up or completed, especially those
which can help the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
It would provide adequate funds for these projects and details
were being worked out by the Finance Ministry, Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He said the critical areas identified under this fund are
public transport, sewerage, solid wastes and water supply.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the fund would be raised through issuing bonds at
home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
He said a committee would be established to manage the fund
which would disburse the money in the form of loans and not
grants.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the establishment of the fund showed Malaysia is
loosening its monetary policy, Anwar said: "It is not necessarily
so because our (monetary) policy is quite consistent but of course
now we are grappling with some immediate problems."
</P>
<P>
He said the on-going projects have to be continued and the
government does not want Bank Negara (state bank)'s credit plan of
a loan growth of 15 percent for this year to be affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
