<HEADLINE> Chinese Private Firms Contribute to Anti-Poverty Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- By the end of 1997, 2,296 private
entrepreneurs had participated in a nationwide anti-poverty
campaign known as the Glorious Cause, which was launched by the
All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce (ACFIC) in 1994.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, 2,731 Glorious Cause projects had been
implemented involving 5.16 billion yuan. The projects helped
547,100 poor people rise above the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
A large number of laborers also have found jobs because of
Glorious Cause. This was learned from an international symposium
on non-governmental poverty-eradication programs held in Beijing
today.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was sponsored by the United Nations Regional
Development Center, the State Council Research Center on
Development, and the China Council For Promotion of Glorious Cause
(CCPGC).
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhaoguo, vice-chairman of the national committee of the
Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) and Chairman of CCPGC, told the
participants that China has made great achievements in eliminating
poverty since the country started its reform, opening-up and
modernization drive in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The four years' experience of Glorious Cause shows that the
program is an effective, vigorous non-governmental way to fight
poverty in coordination with the governmental poverty-eradication
programs, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Also present at today's symposium was Jing Shuping,
vice-chairman of CPPCC and chairman of ACFIC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
