<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Clinton Visits Shanghai Private Housing Estate (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A visit to individual homeowners
in this industrial and financial hub in China has revived U.S.
President Clinton's happy memory of buying his first house and
marrying Ms. Hillary two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to say to all of you who are moving into new
home: Gong Xi! Gong Xi! Congratulations!" the President made a
bilingual greeting to a gathering of some 400 residents when he
visited Jinhui Gardens, a private housing estate in southwest
Shanghai, this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"So I hope that your homes bring you as much joy as mine did 20
years ago," said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Most of the nearly 7,000 residents who have moved into the
Jinhui Gardens, where a private apartment costs between 350,000
and 800,000 RMB yuan (42,200-96,500 US dollars), are
middle-level-income people, including office workers, businessmen
and relatives of overseas Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The president, who has a tight schedule for his two-day stay in
Shanghai, arrived at the estate at about 3:00 p.m., and was warmly
received by the family of Yu Jianyuan, an average household at
Jinhui luckily chosen as host of the presidential visit to a home
apartment.
</P>
<P>
Yu, 35, purchased the four-bedroom, two-sitting-room apartment
in 1997 with family savings, 60,000 yuan (7,500 US dollars) of
provident fund loans and a bank mortgage for 300,000 yuan (36,000
US dollars). She now lives in it with her husband, their
ten-year-old son and her mother.
</P>
<P>
The president had a close look at each room in Yu's apartment,
and praised that they have all been very nicely decorated. He was
quite impressed by the elegant wooden floor in the rooms, saying
that even back in the U.S. not many households have floored their
houses with wood because of its high cost.
</P>
<P>
In the family kitchen, Yu told President Clinton that the
Chinese way of cooking, mostly frying, often causes a lot of
fumes, making everything in the kitchen easy to get dirty.
Clinton said that no wonder they have fixed a fume extractor.
</P>
<P>
Seeing the U.S. president show great interest in a set of
body-building equipment in the study, Yu explained that her
husband is a bit overweight and needs more physical exercises.
Clinton beamed and said that maybe he also needs to buy one when
he is back home.
</P>
<P>
Yu has provided her son with the largest bedroom in her
apartment. Seeing this, Clinton said that it was the same
treatment he received from his mother during his childhood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Clinton Visits Shanghai Private Housing Estate (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When he was about to leave, President Clinton signed autographs
on a family photo of his hostess, as well as on a group photo of
Yu's son and his classmates.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also posed for a picture with the Yu family, saying
that he hopes they will remember this day whenever they see this
photo.
</P>
<P>
The president was then escorted by the family to the courtyard
of the estate, where a makeshift stage had been erected for him to
deliver a speech to the nearly 400 Jinhui residents and a group of
local bankers and real estate developers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that owning their own homes would prompt the
people to work harder, thus contributing to a country's prosperity
and social stability.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Muyao, deputy mayor of Shanghai who accompanied Clinton to
the estate, told the president that Shanghai started to reform its
residents' housing system in the early 1990s, being one of the
country's earliest.
</P>
<P>
"Since 1993, one third of the local families have bought their
own houses by means of seeking bank loans, paying in installments
or joining the Provident housing fund scheme," he added.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton announced at Jinhui that the U.S. and China
are creating a joint residential building counsel to promote new
technology that is needed for a better and more spacious living
environment for the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that the U.S. Ministry of Commerce has been
discussing with related Chinese government agencies the matter on
offering mortgage management expertise to China.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation in this respect focuses on "how to finance people
to buy home from strengthening property rights to developing the
mortgage market," according to the president.
</P>
<P>
"I'm determined to build strong partnership and friendship
between the United States and China that will absolutely make a
positive difference in people's life," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
