<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Land Reform Needs $2.2bn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's land acquisition program
will need 40 billion Zimbabwean Dollars (about 2.2 billion U.S.
Dollars) to resettle more than 100,000 families on one million
hectares annually over five years, a cabinet minister said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister without Portfolio Joseph Msika said the program would
focus on communal farmers interested in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Msika said this during a press conference here when he
unveiled the resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
He said the 40 billion Zimbabwean Dollars would cover
compensation, infrastructural development, input and extension
support.
</P>
<P>
The government, Msika reiterated, would not compensate farmers
for the land, but infrastructural developments on the farms.
</P>
<P>
"We will only consider paying them full compensation after the
donor conference to be held early october if it yields some
seeds," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot tax our people to pay for the land that was not
bought from them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Msika said the British government was now expressing the
desire to help Zimbabwe with its land reform program.
</P>
<P>
The donor conference was postponed from June to September to
allow donors, especially in the European Union, to discuss the
government's policy document on land.
</P>
<P>
The government had also finalized a document with guidelines
to assist resettled farmers to borrow money from banks for
development projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
The land reform and resettlement program will start
immediately without waiting for the donors conference, Msika
said.
</P>
<P>
He said so far 111 farms covering 239,203 hectares had since
been made available to the government, with resettlement already
underway on 12 farms which had been serviced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
