<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The Tunisian Investment Promotion Foundation expects
an increase of 345 million U.S. dollars in investment in the
chemical industry in the next two years, namely, the last two
years of the ninth development plan (1997 - 2001).
</P>
<P>
A study conducted by the foundation reveals that the number of
chemical plants in Tunisia has risen to 437, including those for
the treatment of phosphates and production of chemical fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The Croatian company Ena Industries Nafti has
recently signed a four-year contract with the Syrian Petroleum
company for oil prospection in an area of 4,900 square kilometers
in the Palmyra area in northeastern Syria.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Syrian company said that preliminary estimate
of oil reserves in the fields under prospection is some 200
million barrels, of which 80 million barrels have already been
pumped. The company is planning to produce about 21.2 million
barrels this year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Four international companies specialized in the field
of communications are competing for a deal to build a network of
modern communications for the Suez Canal Authority, the Egyptian
newspaper Alam Al Yom reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The network, which will cost 4 million dollars, covers three
areas along the Suez Canal, namely Ismailia, Port Tewfiq and Port
Said. It will install advanced telecommunications systems,
exchanges and wireless stations for the areas.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Minister of Electricity and Energy Mahir
Abaza has said that the government plans to increase Egypt's
production of generating equipments and materials by 40 to 80
percent, the Alam Al Yom reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister indicated that this will lead to a 45 percent cut
in the cost of establishing electricity networks and transformer
stations.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Cairo ranks the world's ninth most expensive tourist
town in terms of taxes levied on tourist services, the Middle East
News Agency reported Tuesday, quoting a report by the World Tourism
and Travel Council.
</P>
<P>
The findings are the conclusion of field studies conducted on
50 tourist destinations around the world. Copenhagen topped the
list while Istanbul came last. Thirty-seven of these destinations
have increased their taxes over the past three years, while the
remaining 13 have opted for tax cuts, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
