<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swazis to Vote in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A general election will be
held in the tiny kingdom of Swaziland on October 9, the country's
electoral authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The poll will be held at 55 constituency centers to elect
deputies to the national assembly, the lower house of parliament,
South African Press Association quoted chief electoral officer
Robert Thwala as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nominations of candidates would be submitted at community
meetings on August 8 in each of the country's 350 chiefdoms,
Thwala said. Parliament would be dissolved before the nomination
date to enable parliament members and present ministers to
participate in the nomination process.
</P>
<P>
Primary elections in the chiefdoms would take place on
September 12, Thwala said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Swazi constitution, the functions of the country's
bicameral legislature are confined to debating government
proposals and advising the king, who is the head of state and has
supreme executive and legislative power.
</P>
<P>
The national assembly comprises 65 deputies, of whom 55 are
directly elected from candidates nominated by traditional local
councils and 10 appointed by the king.
</P>
<P>
The Senate has 30 members, 20 of whom are appointed by the
king and 10 are elected by the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
Thwala appealed to all Swazis at and above the age of 18 to
register as voters before the registration period ended on July
16.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to political movements, and those calling for a
boycott of the elections in protest to a ban on political
parties, to use their chance to vote for the people they wanted
for the next parliament.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland is the only country in southern Africa not to have
adopted a multi-party democratic system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
