<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1430 GMT, July 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
President Ezer Weizman decided Wednesday to stop accusing each
other in public and to discuss their differences in the future in
private.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders made the remarks in a joint statement after
their meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Weizman and Netanyahu soured when Weizman,
accusing the government of failing to make progress in the Middle
East peace process, called Monday for the Knesset (parliament) to
be dissolved and new general elections held "as soon as possible."
(Israel-Netanyahu-Weizman)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH, WEST BANK -- The Palestinian people will fight to the
end to protect Jerusalem and fight against Israel's Jerusalem
expansion plan, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a special session of the Palestinian Legislative
Council on Israel's Jerusalem plan, Arafat said the battle for
Jerusalem is one of life and death and the Palestinians will not
surrender in getting the city back to the hands of the the
Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
East Jerusalem was seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war
and remains a explosive issue in the peace process. Israel regards
the whole Jerusalem as its capital, but the Palestinians want to
build their independent state with its capital in East Jerusalem.
(Israel-Arafat-Jerusalem)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- A military clash between Kosovo separatists and
Yugoslavia's frontier force occurred in the boder area between
Yugoslavia and Albania on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 10 Kosovo separatists were killed in the clash which
took place early Tuesday in the border area of Djakovica, the
"Politics" newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Many separatists were wounded and fled back to Albania, said
the paper. (Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Military Conflict)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- United Nations Secretary-General Hofi Annan and his
Commonwealth counterpart Emeka Anyaoku have met with Nigerian new
leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar on the country's transition to
democracy process.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said Annan met with Abubakar at the Aso Rock
presidential house in Abuja behind closed doors from 11:45 a.m.
to 1:00 p.m., while Anyaoku's meeting lasted from 4:10 p.m. to
5:20 p.m.
</P>
<P>
General Abubakar and his guests took pictures after the talks
but none spoke with the press on issues discussed.
(Nigeria-Annan's Visit) 
</P>
</TEXT>
