<HEADLINE> Yangtze's Water Flow Hits Second Historical High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Water flow on the main stream of
the section of the Yangtze River running through east China's
Jiangsu Province reached a second historical high for 50 years
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains in Jiangxi and Hunan provinces and other
localities on the middle reaches of the Yangtze since mid-June
have immensely increased the river's water flow.
</P>
<P>
On June 30, the Yangtze's water flow reached 77,600 cubic
meters per second, an amount smaller only than the water flow in
1954 when there were exceptionally severe floods.
</P>
<P>
The water level along the Yangtze's Jiangsu section exceeded
the warning line on June 30, with the tidemarks at Nanjing and
Zhenjiang reaching 9.88 meters and 7.97 meters, about 1.38 meters
and 1.17 meters above their respective safety levels.
</P>
<P>
The high- water level has been further compounded by pouring
rains during what is called the plum rain season on the Chinese
lunar calendar, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Official forecasts say that the Yangtze's water flow will
continue to increase in the near future, making the already severe
task of flood control even more formidable.
</P>
<P>
The Jiangsu provincial government has issued an urgent circular
urging all areas to take prompt measures to counter
floods. Currently, the province's eight cities and 21 counties
along the Yangtze have mobilized a total of 300,000 people for the
flood-control endeavor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
