<HEADLINE> Singapore Stock Closes Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Stock Market
climbed up Wednesday amid optimism that Japan would take effective
measures to put its economy in order.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) gained
28.44 points to close at 1,095.10 points.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover was 144.84 million shares, valued at 251.90
million Singapore dollars (about 149.05 million U.S. dollars).
Gainers led losers by 214 to 89 with 285 stocks remaining
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
SingTel remained the most active stock which had 10.20 million
shares traded. It was followed by DBS Land which had 10.13 million
units done. Wing T was next with 6.38 million shares changing
hands.
</P>
<P>
SPH topped gainers of the day as it rose by 70 cents to close
at 12.00 Singapore dollars. Creative 50 was up 50 cents to finish
at 21.00 Singapore dollars. CityDev gained 43 cents to end at 5.10
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, MICS F was the biggest lower as it shed 46
cents to finish at 2.46 Singapore dollars. Apac Brew was down 28
cents to end at 3.68 Singapore dollars. NatBroad was next as it
fell by 25 cents to close at 0.75 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealors said the rise was due to gains in the Japanese yen, the
Nikkei's strength as well as fresh funds entering the Singapore
market at the start of the new quarter.
</P>
<P>
Gains were seen largely in blue chips with banking and property
shares taking the lead. 
</P>
