<HEADLINE> 5000 Somalis Attend Peace Rally in Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A large peace rally was held
Wednesday in Mogadishu, aimed at praying Allah to bring peace and
stability to Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The rally were attended by more than 5000 people including the
most popular religious scholars from Islamic courts
and intellectuals in the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to the former chairman of north Mogadishu's
collapsed lslamic courts, Sheikh Ali Sheikh Mohamud (Sheikh Ali
dhere), who addressed the crowd, the gathering was organized so
as to revive the spirit of reconciliation among the Somalis in
the capital and the country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Ali Dhere said it's now time that the Somalis are
to forgive each other and work together towards the
reconnaissance of the law and order.
</P>
<P>
The dignitaries who also addressed the crowd include Mrs
Ruqia sheikh Abdullahi who recited an emotional poem over the
grievances of the civil strive and the consequences of the lack
of law and order.
</P>
<P>
Ruqia was followed by Maki Hagi Banadir, a famous comedian,
who also read a Rer Hamar poem over the current status of the
capital which the people had applauded for.
</P>
<P>
The religious scholars have appealed the faction leaders to
honor their words and fulfill their agreements especially the
establishment of an all inclusive administration for the
capital including the re-opening of the air and seaports which
remained out of use since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The rally, sponsored by the recently formed peace Network and
pressure groups, was earlier planned to take place at
Mogadishu's largest mosque near the parliament at the heart of
the city.
</P>
<P>
The rally, the largest peace rally after the consecutive peace
demonstrations that followed the arrival of the faction leaders
from Egypt following their agreement in Cairo late December last
year, coincided with the Independence Day of Somalia, July 1,
(when the Somali-Italians of the South had united with the
Somli-Britain of the North in 1960).  
</P>
