<HEADLINE> Guilin Retains Beauty after Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Guilin City, a tourist attraction in
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, has retained its
scenic beauty after a serious flood fell upon it late last month.
</P>
<P>
The city looks as appealing as before, with clean streets
bathing in the bright sun. And large numbers of Chinese and
foreign tourists have been seen flocking to nearby scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
On June 24, a big flood never seen in the past century
inundated two-thirds of the streets in the urban area of Guilin.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several days, local residents and People's
Liberation Army troops quickly cleaned up the streets and the
Lijiang River to restore the city's beautiful landscape.
</P>
<P>
Lu Shihong, general manager of the Guilin International Travel
Agency, said that his agency received more than 5,000 overseas
tourists mainly from Europe, the United Sates, Japan, Southeast
Asia countries or regions after the flooding.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, one of the major topics among the local residents has
been U.S. President Bill Clinton's upcoming tour of Guilin.
</P>
