<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Think-Tank Tries to Revamp Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's big figures in the tourism
circle gathered Wednesday to find ways to reverse a three-year
downward trend in the sector and to restore the prestige of Kenya
as one of Africa's most attractive destinations.
</P>
<P>
"The downward trend of the sector has been evident for the
last three years" and now it's the time to seek "ways and means
of providing a turn-around point for Kenya's tourism and charting
the way forward," said Kenyan Tourism Minister Henry Kosgey.
</P>
<P>
He told 155 delegates at the Kenya National Tourism Conference
that security, road mending, market research and promotion, as
well as the diversification of product range and source markets
should be listed among top priorities in such bids.
</P>
<P>
"This conference is taking place at a time when we have
experienced the worst tourism decline in the history of our
tourism industry," he sighed.
</P>
<P>
Tourism in Kenya has suffered a lot due to political riots
prior to December's multi-party poll, the post-election tribal
killings in the Rift Valley, disease outbreaks and a general
breakdown of the infrastructure caused by El Nino rains.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Tourist Board predicted losses amounting to some 283
million Dollars by this month, but industry sources said the
figure could be even higher.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, considered a modest year, the industry raked in 433
million Dollars, but this fell o 133 million Dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
At the conference to end Thursday, Kosgey also called for more
attention paid to the environmental issues in attempts to
"cultivate a newly defined image of Kenya's tourism."
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government "has set a new target of over two
million visitors by the year 2002. We should all suggest ways of
protecting our environment to make it possible to sustain such a
number of tourist," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Delegates at the meeting suggested setting up a tourism
investment fund, speeding up road repairing, putting an end to
visa fees, drawing up a code of conducts, and giving land rights
to scheduled international airlines.
</P>
<P>
The European Union Tuesday released a long-term financial
support plan worth two billion Shillings (333 million Dollars) to
help get the country's tourism back on normal track.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent EU survey, Kenya's tourism industry
generates 18 percent of exports and foreign currency earnings,
9.2 percent of gross national product and 11 percent of tax
revenues. It also creates some 56,000 job opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
