<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E.U. Moves on Ozone Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive arm of the European Union, adopted a proposal on
Wednesday for a new regulation on ozone depleting substances
(ODS), as a final step in eliminating ODS.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, which needs approval by the European council of
ministers and the European Parliament, seeks to ban, by the year
2001, production and use of the pesticide methyl bromide.
</P>
<P>
European Environment Commissioner Ritt Bjerregaard described
the proposal as the E.U.'s final step in eliminating all ozone
depleting substances.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation is expected to bring about significant
environmental benefits through reduced future emissions of ODS.
</P>
<P>
Despite a global consensus on the first controls over the ODS,
under the Montreal Protocol ten years ago, ozone losses of up to
40 percent have been observed over northern Europe during recent
winter seasons.
</P>
<P>
Ozone depletion leads to increased ultra-violet radiation which
can cause skin cancers and cataracts, reduces growth of crops and
harms both aquatic and terrestial ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
Ozone depletion is expected to peak during the next decade.
but recovery will not take place until after 2050. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
