<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- An American F-16 jet fighter fired a missile at an Iraqi
anti-aircraft battery because the Iraqi forces had aimed radar at
one of four British jets patroling the "no flight" zone over
southern Iraq, officials in Washington said.
</P>
<P>
-- fighting between Serbian forces and rebels in Kosovo was
heavy, as senior Serbian officials vowed to drive the rebels from
a town near the provincial capital. American officials denounced
the violence.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Linda R. Tripp, the Pentagon employee who secretly recorded
Minica S. Levinsky's laments about an alleged affair with
President Clinton and then turned the tapes over to independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr, made her long-anticipated debut before a
grand jury Tuesday in the investigation she set in motion five
months ago.
</P>
<P>
-- Since 1940, the United States has spent 5.8 billion U.S.
dollars on nuclear weapons programs, more than on any single
program except Social Security, According to a study billed as the
first comprehensive audit of the country's effort to build a
nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Volkswagen and Volvo are in preliminary talks on a
cooperation pact that could eventually lead to a merger, according
to people familiar with the situation. Volvo could help VW enter
the market for medium and heavy trucks. The talks between leaders
of Germany's VW and Sweden's Volvo are the latest sign of
consolidation in the global auto industry.
</P>
<P>
-- In a panel discussion in Shanghai, President Clinton adopted
the three-point formulation Beijing has long pressed the U.S. to
accept regarding Taiwan. Clinton's unequivocal statement is a blow
to Taipei, which relies on U.S. ambiguity as it fends off
reunification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
