<HEADLINE> Porcelain Kettles Commemorate Return of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A set of porcelain kettles made to
commemorate the return of Hong Kong was added to the collection of
the prestigious National Museum of Chinese History here today.
</P>
<P>
The kettles, collected on the occasion of the first anniversary
of Hong Kong's return to the motherland, were made by China's
leading porcelain artisans based on paintings and calligraphy by
more than 50 celebrities from China's social sciences and arts
community.
</P>
<P>
The kettles, a set of 62 in different sizes, are a combination
of such famous porcelain as blue and white and soft colors.
</P>
<P>
The idea of making the kettles came from a Singapore
businessman whose ancestors are from China. 
