<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat: Palestinians Will Fight for Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAMALLAH, WEST BANK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian people
will fight to the end to protect Jerusalem and fight against
Israel's Jerusalem expansion plan, Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a special session of the Palestinian Legislative
Council on Israel's Jerusalem plan, Arafat said the battle for
Jerusalem is one of life and death and the Palestinians will not
surrender in getting the city back to the hands of the the
Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
East Jerusalem was seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war
and remains a explosive issue in the peace process. Israel regards
the whole Jerusalem as its capital, but the Palestinians want to
build their independent state with its capital in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no peace, no security and no stability in
Jerusalem without it being returned to the Palestinians," Arafat
told the session, which was also attended by the members of the
Executive Committee of the Palestinian Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
This has been Arafat's sharpest reaction to Israel's expansion
plan, which passed through the Israeli cabinet June 21.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for expansion of boundaries expansion east of
Jeruesalem to include the largest Jewish settlement of Ma'ale
Adumim which is located inside the territories of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the announcement of the plan, Palestinian
officials criticized it as the "declaration of war against the
Palestinian people."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian legislature's Wednesday session coincided with
the ongoing debate at the U.N. Security Council about Israel's
Jerusalem expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the U.N. said that the United States and Britain
are leading a diplomatic drive to keep the Security Council from
voting on the plan by asking the Council to issue a presidential
statement.
</P>
<P>
Several Arab member states of the U.N. had lobbied in the
Council, urging it to adopt a resolution criticizing Israel's
Jerusalem expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
According to Oslo Accords, Jerusalem is one of several key
issues to be settled by Israel and Palestinians during the final
status peace talks for a permanent peace agreement and no side
should move to change its status before that. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
