<HEADLINE> UN Official Hails Malawi for Adopting Human </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Human Rights, Mrs. Mary Robinson has hailed the
Malawian government for its "clear commitment to the ideals of
democracy and human rights."
</P>
<P>
In a recent letter to Malawian President, Bakili Muluzi,
Robinson said the passing of the Human Rights Commission Bill by
Malawian Parliament last week is a clear evidence of the
"government's commitment to the ideals of human rights as
enshrined in Malawi's new constitution," the Malawian News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Malawi's 177-seat parliament unanimously passed a Human Rights
Commission Bill last week which the Ministry of Justice Spokesman
said, "marks a major development in the consolidation of the
legislative mechanisms for the protection, promotion and
enforcement of human rights in Malawi."
</P>
<P>
"With the establishment of the Human Rights Commission under
the constitution and with the passing of the supportive bill,
Malawi joins the list of a few democratic countries in
sub-Saharan Africa with an internationally recognized legislative
and institutional framework for national realization of human
rights," said the Justice spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Robinson expressed satisfaction by saying that the Human
Rights Commission Bill is "among the best pieces of legislation
in current international practice governing the status and
functions of such national institutions."
</P>
<P>
She therefore, gave assurance of the United Nations pledge to
assist Malawi through the technical cooperation program already
concluded with Malawi and to support the human rights commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
