<HEADLINE> Netanyahu, Weizman Decide to End Row in Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and President Ezer Weizman decided Wednesday to stop
accusing each other in public and to discuss their differences in
the future in private.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders made the remarks in a joint statement after
their meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the two leaders also agreed to meet more
regularly in the future so as to reach understanding in dealing
with sticking political issues.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Weizman and Netanyahu soured when Weizman,
accusing the government of failing to make progress in the Middle
East peace process, called Monday for the Knesset (parliament) to
be dissolved and new general elections held "as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
The call was seen as an attempt to depose Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
In response, Netanyahu accused Weizman of siding with the Arabs
and placing himself at the head of the left-wing camp by his call
to topple the government.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also stressed that he will not change his stance in
the peace talks, which has been deadlocked for more than a year
over the long-delayed Israeli redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu government, citing security reasons, rejected a
U.S. initiative to hand over 13 percent of the West Bank to the
Palestinians during the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The compromise formula, widely seen as a way to bring the
Israeli-Palestinian talks back on track, has been accepted by the
Palestinians. 
</P>
