<HEADLINE> Tanzania Needs $20m for El-Nino-Hit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 1 (Xinhua) - Tanzania needs some 20
million U.S. Dollars to revamp the economic and social
infrastructure damaged by the just ended El-Nino rains.
</P>
<P>
A report, prepared by the Planning Commission, said that funds
are needed to repair roads, bridges, railways, harbors, airports
and power supply lines which are critical to the national
economic development, media here quoted the report as saying
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The rains severely damaged nine trunk road corridors,
sweeping away about 20 bridges," the report said, giving an
example of the El-Nino destruction.
</P>
<P>
It calls for permanent measures to be taken to upgrade the
infrastructure installations including the capacity to respond to
emergency situations to prevent or minimize damages in disasters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report projects that the economic growth for
1998/99 fiscal year would not rise above 3.5 percent, a steep
fall from the earlier forecast of about five percent.
</P>
<P>
"Also forecast is a significant drop in the production of cash
crops like coffee, cashewnuts and cotton," the report said.
"However, there could be a bumper food crops harvest,
particularly for maize, rice, bananas, potatoes and beans."
</P>
<P>
The production of livestock and by-products like milk and
skins is expected to register a significant growth following the
availability of adequate pasture and water, the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
