<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Palestinians Growing Frustrated: Poll Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half of the Palestinians
are now frustrated with the stalled peace process and support
violence against Israelis, which is a four-year high, a
Palestinian poll indicated.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted by the Nablus-based Center for Palestine
Research and Studies (CPRS) last week, showed that as many as 49.7
percent of the people questioned support "armed attacks against
Israelis."
</P>
<P>
Israeli newspaper Haaretz Wednesday quoted CPRS Director Khalil
Shikaki as saying that the support for hardline stance jumped 10
percent in the last six months alone and more than doubled the 22
percent before Likud coalition government took power in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Shikaki said the poll, whose results will be formally released
soon, indicated the growing frustration among the Palestinians
over the stalled the peace process,
</P>
<P>
He said the poll demonstrates a regression in Palestinians'
acceptance of the idea that non-violence means will move the peace
process forward.
</P>
<P>
"Between 1994 and 1996, the peace process transformed the
Palestinian psychological environment, leading more and more
Palestinians to support negotiations and oppose terrorism. This
has now been reversed," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is now a clear trend that a majority of Palestinians do
not believe that the peace process alone - though it still has 68
percent support - will bring about the resolution of the
conflict," he added.
</P>
<P>
Shikaki noted that between 1994 and 1996, 44.8 percent of
the Palestinians public opposed terror attacks against Israel and
in early 1996, 68 percent of Palestinians supported a crackdown
against Hamas after a wave of terror against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The survey, interviewing 1,300 Palestinians from the West Bank
and Gaza, also showed 50.5 percent of the Palestinians opposed the
U.S. initiative calling for a 13.1 percent Israeli troops
withdrawal from the West Bank, while 43 percent supported it.
</P>
<P>
With this 13.1 percent, the Palestinians will have under their
control 40 percent of the West Bank. But the growing discontent
showed "Palestinians think it is too little, too late," Shikaki
said.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) may also be somewhat
at fault, since it built up expectations that it would obtain 90
percent of the territories. So there is disappointment," he added.
</P>
<P>
And only 6 percent of the Palestinians believed in the
sincerity of the current Israeli government, the poll showed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the poll indicated that support for the reelection
of PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat dropped by 10 percent over the last
six months to 61 percent, but he still dwarfed Hamas leader Sheikh
Ahmed Yassin, who commands a paltry 2 percent of support.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the poll showed that Hamas has not benefited from
the anti-Israel mood, as its support rate remains basically
steady at 13.5 percent in comparison with the equally stable 43
percent of support rate for Arafat's Fatah, the mainstream of the
Palestinian Liberation Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
