<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Committed to Eliminating Poverty Before Century Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Wang Zhaoguo, vice chairman of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference, said here today that China is committed to eliminating
poverty by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an international seminar on non-governmental
poverty-relief efforts that opened here today, Wang said
eliminating poverty and realizing common prosperity have been two
goals long pursued by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government unveiled in 1994 a state strategic plan
to ensure that the impoverished have the basic means of
subsistence -- to be able to feed and clothe themselves -- by
2,000.
</P>
<P>
In the last four years, Wang said, the poor rural population in
China has been reduced to 50 million from around 80 million in
1994.
</P>
<P>
Apart from government endeavors, various social groups have
played a significant role in reducing poverty, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who is also president of the China Association for the
Promotion of the Glorious Cause, a non-governmental
poverty-alleviation organization set up in 1995, said the
association has attracted about 2,300 private business people who
have started 2,700 projects in poor areas and helped lift more
than 500,000 out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Wang expressed his hope that international organizations like
the United Nations Development Program, the World Bank and
humanitarian bodies should continue their support for China's
poverty-relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 people -- including experts, scholars and
entrepreneurs from the United Nations, Japan, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Thailand, the Philippines and India -- were present at the seminar
to discuss issues and exchange experiences concerning poverty
elimination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
