<HEADLINE> Clinton Has Exclusive Interview with CCTV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton said today that the biggest achievement of his visit to
China is the further deepening of understanding between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that during this visit, leaders of both countries
recognized that the two countries have a common future.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the remarks in an exclusive interview with the
China Central Television (CCTV) in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president said that during his visit, the two
countries have made new progress in a series of aspects with
regard to building a cooperative strategic partnership that is
oriented to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
He said that the agreement between the two countries on
de-targeting nuclear weapons under their respective control at
each other's country is "very important."
</P>
<P>
He said that mutual trust between the two countries has been
greatly improved. The agreement demonstrates the firm
determination of the United States and China to prevent
proliferation of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
He said this will help strengthen peace and stability in the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
He noted that another achievement in his visit is the further
expansion of U.S.-China cooperation in the fields of trade,
science and technology, energy, law and environment.
</P>
<P>
Noting that a dramatic economic development is going on in
China, he said that China is opening wider and wider to the
outside world in terms of education.
</P>
<P>
He is impressed with the Chinese people's pursuit of high
technology and information, Clinton said, adding that young
Chinese are working for a better life.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is excited to see all these.
</P>
<P>
A segment of his interview with CCTV was aired this evening and
CCTV said that the full text of the interview will be aired
tomorrow evening.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived in Xi'an on June 25 on a nine-day, five-city
state visit to China and Shanghai is the third leg after his
visit to Xi'an and Beijing. He is scheduled to fly to the
picturesque city of Guilin in Southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region tomorrow.  
</P>
