<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU-Moldova Cooperation Accord Comes Into Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union-Moldova
partnership and cooperation agreement came into force on
Wednesday, furthering EU support to the country's transition to a
market economy.
</P>
<P>
Moldova has thus become the third country among the former
Soviet republics to have a partnership and cooperation accord with
the 15-nation union.
</P>
<P>
Between 1991 and this year, overall EU financial support to
Moldova amounted to 126 million ECU.
</P>
<P>
The partnership and cooperation agreement, reached in November
1994, is to focus on further developing political and economic
dialogue between the EU and Moldova.
</P>
<P>
It aims to foster trade and investment by reciprocal
commitments to ensure freedom of trade, non-discrimination of
foreign companies, liberalization of capital transfers and by
providing groundwork for cooperation on the environment,
cross-border and customs issues, transport, education and
intellectual property protection.
</P>
<P>
In support of these aims, the EU promised to continue with
technical assistance to Moldova, with a focus on human resources
development, private sector development and food production,
processing and distribution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
