<HEADLINE> Swiss UBS to Sell Private Bank to Italian Insurer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The new UBS Group plans to sell a
private bank and an information technology company to an Italian
insurer, Assicurazioni Generali SpA, the UBS announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The private bank to be sold, Banca della Swizzera Italiana, is
based in Switzerland's Italian-speaking city of Lugano. Also
included in the transaction plan is the information technology
company, BOSS LAB SA.
</P>
<P>
The plan needs to be approved by both Swiss and Italian
supervisory authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss UBS bank expects that the transaction, worth 1.92
billion Swiss francs (about 1.27 billion U.S. dollars), will
contribute an additional profit of about one billion Swiss francs
(about 670 million U.S. dollars) to the group's 1998 results.
</P>
<P>
The new UBS, from the merger of Union Bank of Switzerland and
Swiss Bank Corp, officially came into being over the weekend. It
is Europe's biggest bank and the third largest in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
