<HEADLINE> Prodi: No Obstacle in Promoting Rome-Tehran Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi said here on Wednesday that no obstacle stands in the
way of expanding relations with Iran, and the friendship between
the two countries will help promote cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with Iran's First Vice President Hassan Habibi,
Prodi said the two countries have always had good relations,
especially in the economic fields, the official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
Habibi said that Italy will continue being a friend of Iran and
the current visit by the high ranking Italian delegation is of
great importance for both sides. He expressed the hope that during
Prodi's stay here, the two countries' officials can tackle all
issues of mutual interests.
</P>
<P>
There are ample grounds on which the two countries can build
cooperation and all the avenues should be explored to this end, he
said, adding that Iran wants to cooperate with Italy in economy
and industry.
</P>
<P>
Prodi arrived here Tuesday night for a two-day official visit,
the first one by a European head of government since the Iran's
1979 Islamic Revolution. He was formally welcomed at a ceremony
held by Habibi earlier Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Prodi expressed his confidence at the ceremony that his visit
will open a new chapter in Rome-Tehran ties, saying that the trip
is not limited to promoting bilateral economic ties but is
important for political cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Habibi said that Prodi's visit "has an
international message," adding that he was pleased with the fact
some European countries have now changed their outlook and
approach towards Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that both Iran and Italy have ancient civilizations,
and Iran believes that this heritage can serve future cooperation
among Islam, Christianity as well as all countries interested in
peace and tranquillity. 
</P>
