<HEADLINE> Amended Forestry Law Going Into Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The amended Forestry Law of the
People's Republic of China went into enforcement today to
replace the old law in place for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhibao, director of the State Forestry Administration,
said that the new law will not only contribute greatly to the
protection and development of China's forestry resources, but will
also improve the nation's.
</P>
<P>
China adopted a pilot forestry law in 1979, with the old
forestry law going into effect on January 1, 1985.
</P>
<P>
The amended forestry law underlines the protection and
management of forestry law resources, and will both establish a
compensation fund for forest ecology and provide new financial
sources for reforestation and landscaping programs, Wang noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, the amended law also strengthen protection
of the nation's precious plant species.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Wang acknowledged that the amended law and the new
Criminal Law stipulate heavy penalties for the destruction of
forestry law resources.
</P>
<P>
The director urged the related forestry law departments to
amend existing codes and regulations to coincide with the new
forestry law law, and to "enforce their work to protect the
nation's forestry law resources".
</P>
<P>
China's forest coverage currently stands at 14 percent,
according to a recent government bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has also announced a decision to halt
timbering in natural forests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Human Rights Chief "Deeply Concerned" Over Expulsions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- United Nations High Commissioner for
Human Rights (UNHCHR) Mrs Mary Robinson has expressed deep concern
over the continuing expulsion of Eritrean nationals from Ethiopia,
saying the actions are serious violations of human rights.
</P>
<P>
"I am deeply concerned by the violation of human rights of
Eritrean nationals being expelled from Ethiopia, and particularly
by the fact that their passports are being stamped 'expelled,
never to return'," Robinson said in a statement issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, others who had been trying to leave have had
their identity cards confiscated, she said..
</P>
<P>
"These are serious violations of the rights and freedoms set
forth in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, as well as in
the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, to which
Ethiopia is a party," she said.
</P>
<P>
The high commissioner appealed to the governments of Ethiopia
and Eritrea "to look urgently at ways of restoring dialogue with
each other".
</P>
<P>
"I also call upon the government of Ethiopia to respect the
rights of non-discrimination and freedom of movement, and to meet
its obligations under the international covenants and other human
rights treaties it has ratified," she said.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of May, armed conflict triggered by the
long-term territorial dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea, turned
violent, killing dozens of civilians and displacing tens-of-
thousands of others in the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
