<HEADLINE> New Members of Indonesia's People's Consultative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 39 new members of
Indonesia's People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) were sworn in at
a ceremony here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
President B.J. Habibie on Tuesday appointed 41 new members of
MPR to replace those retired by him or who had resigned or passed
away. However, two of them refused to accept the appointment.
</P>
<P>
There was no explanation about the decision to retire the old
members, all of whom were selected by former president Soeharto
from functional groups to represent the ruling Golkar party.
</P>
<P>
But the decision was seen by the local press as a surprising
political move aimed at restructuring the MPR, the country's
highest legislative body.
</P>
<P>
A number of MPR members have resigned following public pressure
to cleanse the assembly of all elements of corruption, collusion
and nepotism. Those who already tendered their resignation include
the wives and children of serving or former government officials.
But the children of Soeharto have resisted calls for them to
resign.
</P>
<P>
The 41 nominations were within the 100 which the president has
the right to empty or fill under existing laws. The 1,000-member
MPR is made up of elected parliamentarians and a slightly greater
number of appointed members.
</P>
<P>
Names of the new members listed by Habibie include several
ministers from his cabinet, two prominent figures from the ethnic
Chinese Indonesian community and a human rights activist, among
others.
</P>
<P>
The new faces are figures free from corruption, collusion and
nepotism, said MPR Deputy Speaker Abdul Gafur.
</P>
<P>
The list of those retired includes a number of cabinet
ministers who had served under Soeharto, who stepped down on May
21 amid mounting pressure for his resignation as the country
plunged into a political and economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ousted members include several members of MPR's working
committee, former home minister R. Hartono and former finance
minister Fuad Bawazier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
