<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Investigates Grain Bureau for Fund Diversion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A grain bureau in northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province has been investigated for misusing grain
procurement funds and two officials found accountable have been
dismissed from their posts.
</P>
<P>
Investigations based on clues provided by the public have shown
that the Suihua City Grain Bureau, in Heilongjiang Province,
diverted a total of 91.91 million yuan in funds for purchasing
grain and edible oil between September 1996 and May this year.
</P>
<P>
A news release on the investigation said that, in September of
1996, the grain bureau decided by itself to move some 100,000 tons
of grain, including 970,000 tons of corn, from its subsidiary
storages to be stored in Dalian, a coastal city in Liaoning
Province. The grain was valued at 120 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
To hide the facts, the bureau did not make any financial
booking about the grain movement or entered the transfer into the
account book. Instead, it opened an account at the city branch of
the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China in violation of
government rules.
</P>
<P>
Later the bureau sold the corn, at prices lower than the
purchasing prices, to the Guangdong Huaqiao Youyi Corporation, in
southern Guangdong Province, to Harbin Daoli District Food Market
and to some other buyers, and then deposited into its bank account
the 95.87 million yuan obtained from the deal.
</P>
<P>
Of the cash amount, the bureau used 40.99 million yuan to
construct a hotel, an office building and residential housings,
lent 48 million yuan to its subsidiary grain enterprises and goods
and materials companies, used 936,000 million yuan to buy
automobiles, and spent the remaining 1.92 million yuan for other
purposes.
</P>
<P>
Besides fund diversion, the bureau has also been found to buy
goods and materials for construction of grain storage facilities
in excess of the official limit in exchange for 276,900 yuan in
kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
The Heilongjiang provincial government has paid close attention
to the fund diversion issue. It has decided to auction off the
hotel and residential housings built with the diverted funds and
use the money from the auction to pay back loans from the local
branch of the Agricultural Development Bank of China, a policy
bank specialized in the extension of loans for grain procurement.
</P>
<P>
The director of the grain bureau and the president of the
branch bank have been dismissed from their posts. Investigation of
the bureau's problems will continue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
