<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African FMs Worried over Situation in Angola, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers from
Portuguese-Speaking African countries who were meeting in Sao
Tome &AMP; Principe have expressed worries over the current situation
in Angola and Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued Tuesday after the one-day meeting, the
ministers called for a complete disarmament by the National Union
for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) and an unconditional
demobilization of its remnant militiamen, the Angola News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also appreciated the Angolan government's
flexibility in postponing the deadline to June 30 for UNITA to
finish the tasks prescribed in the Lusaka Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
They believed that if UNITA fails to meet the deadline, the
United Nations Security Council sanctions will immediately take
effect.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers also expressed their deep condolences to
the death of Alioune Blondin Beye, the U.N. special envoy to
Angola in a plane crash, appealing to the international community
to redouble efforts to ensure the peace agreement in Angola be
implemented so as to avoid a reoccurrence of civil war there.
</P>
<P>
The meeting condemned the armed mutiny in Guinea Bissau,
stressing that dialog should be a first choice in dealing with
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ministers urged that a rule of law must be restored in the
west African country in a bid to respect the democratically
elected government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports said the funeral ceremony of Beye was held
Tuesday in his home country of Mali. Angolan government, the
opposition UNITA, United Nations, and Portugal, United States and
Russia and some African countries have sent representatives to
pay their last respects to Beye who had devoted his life to the
peace in Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
