<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. President Clinton Visits Shanghai Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton this noon visited the Shanghai Stock Exchange (SSE), the
first of its kind in China.
</P>
<P>
Amid the applause of more than 1,000 traders wearing red vests,
Clinton entered the major transaction hall of the stock exchange
at about 12:10 (local time) in the company of Shanghai Mayor Xu
Kuangdi.
</P>
<P>
Threading his way through the crowd of traders, the majority of
them being young people, the president inquired about trading
matters. Many of them responded in fluent English.
</P>
<P>
SSE General Manager Tu Guangshao said the exchange, established
in December 1990, deals with A-shares, B-shares, funds, treasury
bonds, enterprise bonds and financial bonds, among others.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the twinkling electronic boards, Tu said that by
the end of May this year, 407 enterprises had been listed on the
stock exchange, with 446 kinds of stocks involving a total market
capitalization of 1.1867 trillion yuan (about 143 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
A trader called Chen Chen invited Clinton to sit on his seat
and showed him the way of operation on a computer in front of
him.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of all traders at the exchange, Chen presented
President Clinton with a red vest printed with the figures of
"1998" as a souvenir.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president then went to the seats where a lot of
foreign traders were busy with their B-share transactions.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that he was pleased to have a tour of the stock
exchange, describing the scene there as "exciting."
</P>
<P>
He told the SSE general manager that "you should feel proud of
the success of the stock exchange."  
</P>
</TEXT>
