<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan, Anyaoku Meet Nigerian Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Hofi Annan and his Commonwealth counterpart Emeka Anyaoku have
met with Nigerian new leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar on the
country's transition to democracy process.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said Annan met with Abubakar at the Aso Rock
presidential house in Abuja behind closed doors from 11:45 a.m.
to 1:00 p.m., while Anyaoku's meeting lasted from 4:10 p.m. to
5:20 p.m.
</P>
<P>
General Abubakar and his guests took pictures after the talks
but none spoke with the press on issues discussed.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Chief Press Secretary to the Head of
State, David Attah later quoted Abubakar as saying that Nigeria
would continue to contribute to global peace and security under
the framework of the U.N.
</P>
<P>
He solicited the understanding and cooperation of the
international society in his effort to achieve national
reconciliation, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
According to Attah, the U.N. Secretary-General commended the
steps taken by Abubakar to reconcile the nation particularly the
release of different categories of political detainees.
</P>
<P>
Annan was quoted as saying that "once Nigeria puts her house
in order, she would take its rightful place in the comity of
nations."
</P>
<P>
He commended Nigeria's leadership in the West African
sub-region, especially its contribution in the restoration of
peace in Liberia and democracy in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed the hope that African leaders would do more to
contain the spate of crisis in the continent and focus attention
on the more challenging task of development in order to alleviate
the suffering of the masses, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Commonwealth Secretary-General Anyaoku also
commended Abubakar's action in his short period of leadership,
adding that his organization is ready to help Nigeria in its
transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku said the Commonwealth is anxious to normalize
relations with Nigeria, which he said is an important member of
the organization.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, Annan have also met with officials
of the National Electoral Commission of Nigeria, the National
Human Rights Commission, former leader Yakubo Gowon and Chief
Earnest Shonekan, as part of his effort to understand the
situation in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He also talked on phone with former head of state, General
Olusegun Obasanjo, who was recently released by Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
Annan may have also met with Moshood Abiola, the presumed
winner of the annulled June 12, 1993 presidential election,
before his Wednesday meeting with Abubakar, said a media report,
but that could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived in Nigeria Monday, while Anyaoku arrived a day
before. They are expected to speak to the press Thursday in Abuja
and Lagos, respectively, before ending their visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
