<HEADLINE> Ford to Further Increase Presence in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The world's second largest auto
manufacturer, Ford Motor Company, will expand its cooperation
with Chinese partners in developing alternative fuels and cutting
down auto pollution.
</P>
<P>
Vaughn Koshkarian, Ford vice president and Ford China chairman
and CEO, told Xinhua in an interview today that Ford will further
expand its business presence in China.
</P>
<P>
"Ford has a long history in China, and the cooperation between
Ford and Chinese partners over the past few years have resulted in
outstanding achievements. We very much want to support and
participate in the growth of China's auto industry," he said.
</P>
<P>
So far Ford has set up five joint ventures in China, producing
air conditioners, electronics products, glass, plastic ornaments
and other products used in automobiles, and it also holds shares
in China's Jiangling Motors.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Ford has also built a nationwide service network
with 44 servicing centers throughout China, providing
comprehensive after-sale services for customers.
</P>
<P>
Koshkarian cited Transit, Ford's jointly developed vehicle with
Jiangling, as an example of successful cooperation with Chinese
partners.
</P>
<P>
"The participation of local engineers in auto development very
much helps develop the capability of local manufacturers," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford to Further Increase Presence in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said that Ford has been involved in a lot of research
programs in China, many of which are related to fuel availability,
alternative fuels, rare earth catalysts and environmental
concerns.
</P>
<P>
He added that China is rich in coal resources, and currently
Ford is doing a research study jointly with Chinese partners on
the use of coal as a fuel for transportation.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that China cherishes a huge market for alternative
fuels. Ford has more than 30 years' experience in developing clean
gaseous fuel. This advantage will benefit our Chinese customers
and partners," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ford also pays attention to the training of local technicians,
he said. So far Ford has sent more than 100 people from its
Chinese joint ventures to the United States, Europe and other
locations for training.
</P>
<P>
Ford has also set up technician training schools in Beijing and
Nanchang to train local employees.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the view that, considering the huge population of
1.2 billion, China has great potentials for auto industry
development. In the foreseeable future, China is going to be the
third or fourth largest auto producer in the world, or even the
largest at some points.
</P>
<P>
"The only question is how fast China will become the largest
auto producer in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We see our operation in China as a very important part of
Ford, it's important for us to bring technology and established
product development capability to China," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Ford will continue to play an active role in
China's auto industry, continue to support the enhancement of the
relationship between China and the U.S., and contribute to the
mutual understanding of the two peoples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
