<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Higher With Influx of Cash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market gained
more than one percent on the first day of the new financial year
(1998-99) on Wednesday, as capital flowed into Australia on the
back of a stronger local currency.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished on its high for the day,
adding 31 points to 2699.4 points.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of it (the money coming in) was currency related," Ord
Minnett broker Hamish Bonifant said.
</P>
<P>
A stronger Japanese market also helped with the Nikkei index
climbing 533 points to 16363.0.
</P>
<P>
Diversified miner BHP added around five points to the market
after it bounced 38 cents to 14.03 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index added 39.7 points to 4728.7 while the
all resources index rose 25.8 points to 1063.2.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, ANZ shares jumped 19.8 cents, National
Australia Bank climbed 6.7 cents, Commonwealth rose 20 cents and
Westpac was up 15 cents.
</P>
<P>
The banking index was 55.5 points stronger at 5806.5.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leading insurance group AMP recovered some ground
lost earlier in the week, rocketing 91.7 cents. Fellow insurer
National Mutual jumped 11 cents and Colonial rose seven cents.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, Rio Tinto dipped 20 cents, MIM climbed
two cents, WMC rose 14 cents and North soared 28 cents.
</P>
<P>
In the gold sector, the gold index stacked on 41.3 points to
1096.3 as the gold bullion spot price added 1.10 to 297.40 U.S.
dollars per ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 345.09 million shares worth 1.41 billion
Australian dollars (874.2 million U.S. dollars) with rises
outnumbering falls by 761 to 327. 
</P>
</TEXT>
