<HEADLINE> Ugandan Parliament Okays Govt's Extra Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Fifty billion Uganda shillings (50
million U.S. Dollars) spent by the government and departments in
excess of what had originally been budgeted in the 1997/98
financial year ending Tuesday has been endorsed by Parliament.
</P>
<P>
A New Vision paper report said Wednesday that the government
had budgeted 647.7 billion shillings (647 million Dollars) for
recurrent spending and 749,7 billion shillings (749 million
Dollars) for capital development.
</P>
<P>
It spent 680 billion shillings (680 million Dollars) in the
first field and 755 billion shillings (755 million Dollars) in
the latter, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Although parliament passed the supplementary expenditure
without a quorum, the members of parliament took the Minister of
State for Finance and Economic Planning, Mr. Sam Kutesa, to task
over the excessive spending incurred by State House on President
Yoweri Museveni's foreign and inland travels as well as fuel and
lubricants.
</P>
<P>
Some MPs said the president's trips had increased the State
House expenditure by 4 billion shillings or four million Dollars,
almost one third of the oral budget.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry was also criticized for some inefficiency
in budget management and for preferring to incur supplementary
spendings instead of seeking approval from parliament in advance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
