<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Market anticipation of a package
to fix the ailing Japanese banking sector drove the Australian
dollar almost one U.S. cent higher on the first day of the new
financial year (1998-99).
</P>
<P>
The fickle local currency Wednesday night closed above 62.00
U.S. cents for the first time in over a month. It ended the day
here at 62.27 U.S. cents, from 61.47 late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"To have an Australian dollar closing in Sydney above 62.20
U.S. cents is a strong signal," Commonwealth Bank senior manager
of foreign exchange Kurt Magnus said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Australian dollar was stronger because of four
factors.
</P>
<P>
"The yen is stronger, the prospects for a China devaluation are
much lower, commodities are stronger and there is a better
prospect for Australia's current account," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We see those four things as being critical in keeping the
Australian dollar at some level of support above 62.00 U.S.
cents."
</P>
<P>
Magnus said "the market is concentrating on what the Japanese
yen does and is very closely watching any news on the possibility
of income tax cuts, corporate tax cuts and a rigid, structured
program to bail out their banks," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign exchange market was skeptical as to
whether Japan would make the necessary reforms, Magnus said.
</P>
<P>
If suitable reforms do not eventuate, then the downside risk
will return for both the Australian dollar and the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
"If the Japanese don't come up with the goods, then we are back
to the Australian dollar and the Japanese yen going lower."
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar was trading at 85.79
Japanese yen from 86.14 and 1.1251 German marks from 1.1111.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
