<HEADLINE> Food Shipments to, from Tanzania Checked for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- All importers and exporters
of foodstuffs are requested to send their samples to Tanzanian
National Radiation Commission (NRC) before they are cleared for
distribution in a bid to protect consumers against radiation.
</P>
<P>
A statement reaching here by NRC based in northern Arusha said
Wednesday that the Commission will issue certificates to those
whose products meet its conditions under a Tanzanian Act set to
control radiation contamination on foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
Non-compliance of importers and exporters with the regulations
will be liable to a minimum fine of 10,000 Tanzanian Shillings
(about 15 U.S. Dollars) or a six-month jail sentence, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Commission strongly appeals for your close and maximum
cooperation in the implementation and enforcement for effective
compliance with these regulations," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed by the NRC registrar Abraham Nyanda,
said that the existing free market economy allows imports and
exports of foodstuffs, but most of them lack expiry dates or are
poorly packed.
</P>
<P>
"Neither do they have radiation levels marked on the
containers nor radiation clearance certificates issued," the
statement added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
