<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Government Starts 5-Year Health Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government on
Wednesday started a health and population sector program aimed at
raising efficiency and effectiveness of primary health-care at the
grassroots level across the country.
</P>
<P>
The program was approved recently by the country's Executive
Committee for National Economic Council following negotiations
between the donor consortium led by the World Bank and Bangladeshi
government.
</P>
<P>
The first year of the program, at a cost of 2.9 billion U.S.
dollars, would be a transitional period both in terms of
structuring and functioning.
</P>
<P>
Of the total amount, 2.1 billion dollars would come from the
government's revenue and development budget while the rest would
be funded by the donors.
</P>
<P>
A recent review of the Fourth Population and Health Project,
which officially ended on June 30 this year, by the World Bank
mission in the country said the project has achieved most of its
objectives, particularly those related to reducing fertility,
child mortality, malnutrition and controlling communicable
diseases.
</P>
<P>
However, routine administrative weaknesses, such as frequent
transfer of key officials, delay in releasing of funds, and
inappropriate use of expensive specialized training still
constrained the performance of the project at least in the initial
years, the review said.
</P>
<P>
And little progress was made in such areas as maternal health
service and human resource development which had a "serious effect
on efficiency of service implementation and training program," the
World Bank said.
</P>
<P>
It recommended that effective implementation and close
monitoring of the new program is needed to see continued progress
in maternal health care, human resources development and
structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
As one of the world's poorest countries, child malnutrition is
very common in Bangladesh with nearly half of its 127
million-population living in poverty and a child mortality rate
of about 76 per 1,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
