<HEADLINE> Russians Win Most Prizes at Tchaikovsky Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The 11th International Tchaikovsky
Competition concluded here Tuesday night, with Russian musicians
winning three of the four top prizes and a Japanese snatching the
remaining one.
</P>
<P>
The first prize in piano went to Denis Machuyev, while the
titles for violin and cello were won by Nikolai Sachenko and Denis
Shapovalov respectively.
</P>
<P>
Mica Sato of Japan and Besik Gabitashvili of Georgia went away
with the first and second prizes in the vocals.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Australian Qin Liwei took the second prize in cello,
the first ethnic Chinese to enter the finals of the Tchaikovsky
music competition.
</P>
<P>
Pan Yiqiong and Huang Bin from China won the third and fourth
places in the violin competition.
</P>
<P>
Pan, 17, now studying at the Moscow conservatory named after
P. Tchaikovsky, was awarded the Special Prize for Performance of
German music work.
</P>
<P>
The Tchaikovsky competition has been held every four years
since 1958, launching successful careers for many of the winners.
</P>
<P>
The top prize is 10,000 U.S. dollars, runners-up take 8,000
dollars and third-place finishers get 6,000 dollars. 
</P>
