<HEADLINE> Clinton Defends His China Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
defended his China trip here today by saying that Americans "go
around the world telling people that no one has a monopoly on the
truth...we don't either."
</P>
<P>
There are some people who actually question whether Clinton
ought to have come on this trip and who had prescriptive advice,
"which would have completely undermined the effectiveness of the
trip," according to the president.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to explain to American colleagues and friends
back home the importance of our engagement with China," said
Clinton, who is on the third leg of his nine-day state visit to
China, while meeting a group of entrepreneurs in the largest
Chinese economic center, Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
He has cited in today's as well as earlier talks many important
agreements he reached with his Chinese counterpart, President
Jiang Zemin, during their official talks on June 27 on security
and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
He particularly stressed the important role China has played in
maintaining Asia's economic stability.
</P>
<P>
"I must say that I appreciate the very constructive role China
has played in promoting financial stability in the region, through
direct assistance, multilateral cooperation, participation in the
international institutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We live in a world where the unique position of the United
States...with all our economic strength, is such that we can
maximize our influence only by reaching out a hand of cooperation
as well as standing strong when the moment requires it," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to make most of our progress with most people by
working with them, and that requires us to seek to understand and
communicate and reciprocate and to live by the values we espouse,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have a lot to do to help America and China reach their full
potential in the 21st century," the president noted. 
