<HEADLINE> Share Prices Surge for 6th Straight Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices gained for the sixth
consecutive trading day Wednesday in Tokyo with the key Nikkei
index climbing above 16,000 for the first time since late April.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors rushed to buy steel, banking and construction
issues after a Japanese daily reported that a permanent income tax
cut of 2 trillion to 4 trillion yen (about 14.5 billion dollars to
29.0 billion dollars) is likely next year as part of the
government's effort to boost the sluggish Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 532.62 points, or 3.36
percent, from Tuesday's close to finish at 16,362.89.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all First Section
issues, advanced 40.37 points or 3.28 percent to 1,270.75.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section swelled to an estimated 850
million shares from Tuesday's 576.30 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The yen's recent recovery against the U.S. dollar in currency
markets, as well as the permanent tax cut report, triggered
massive net buying by foreign brokerages, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outpaced decliners 984 to 188. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
