<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Serb forces intensified on Tuesday their attacks on Albanian
separatists who have occupied a coal mine a dozen kilometers from
the Kosovo capital Pristina. The coal mine is the source of
energy for a major thermal station which supplies electricity to
the whole Kosovo province. It also exports coal to Greece and
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli President Ezer Weizman expressed his lack of
confidence in Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu by calling for an
early election which could lead to his departure. This is a rare
intervention by the president of Israel in the history of the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
--The Islamic militant group of Algeria, the Armed Islamic
Group, has claimed responsibility for last week's assassination of
the singer Matoub Lounes. Algerian security forces sealed off the
capital Algiers to the demonstrators who tried to hold protests
against the assassination on Sunday. But people were allowed to
demonstrate in Tizi-Ouzou, the home province of Lounes.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- While unemployment rate in France is dropping, the support
rates for President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin have attained record high, according to latest polls. The
support rate of Chirac now stands at 60 percent, compared with 51
percent in May, and that of Jospin is 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac Tuesday completed his tour in
southern Africa by calling on Africans to adopt the "universal
principle of democracy." In a speech to the Angolan parliament in
Luanda, Chirac said that democracy is the only way to go out of
the "infernal cycle" of violence, oppression and injustice.
</P>
