<HEADLINE> One Million Dollars Invested in Tobacco in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- About one million U.S. Dollars has
been ploughed into various tobacco-related projects in Zambia
this year, according to the International Tobacco Growers
Association (ITGA).
</P>
<P>
The latest ITGA newsletter said that many tobacco farmers,
including small-scale producers, have invested in various
projects, giving a total investment of around one million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
During the current season, five tobacco growers commissioned
new irrigation systems, doubling the previous irritated crop.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it said, five new forced-air curing systems were
also commissioned.
</P>
<P>
The new systems are an interesting development that will
contribute a great deal to the financial viability of tobacco
production.
</P>
<P>
Each development represents an investment of 75,000 to 150,000
Dollars, it said.
</P>
<P>
Many small-scale producers have also invested in
infrastructure to expand their crop programs, according to ITGA.
</P>
<P>
Considering the country's small commercial tobacco-producing
community, Tobacco Association Zambia said these investments are
a notable development reflecting on the confidence of Zambian
farmers on their crop as well as the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
