<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8,000 Mozambicans Legalized in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- At least 8,000 Mozambicans have
been given a legal working status in the past six years in South
Africa, according to Petro Taimo, Mozmabique's Labor Ministry
representative in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The South African authorities are considering legalizing
another 4,000 Mozambicans currently living and working in
Transvaal, in the northern part of South Africa, Taimo was quoted
by Wednesday's Noticias newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mozambicans often complain of their detention in South Africa
and that they could not take back their properties after being
expelled from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Taimo believed that the detention and expulsion cases of
Mozambicans illegally working and living in South Africa are
increasing, due to poor coordination with the South African
Ministry of Home Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"The properties of the expelled should be well handled," he
said, noting that another worrying issue is that the detained
were not given humanitarian treatment in the transition center,
and that South African police were quite ill-mannered with
detained Mozambican citizens.
</P>
<P>
However, Taimo added, he is now consulting with South African
Ministry of Home Affairs and trying to reach an agreement in this
regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
