<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.S., China to Step Up Housing Construction Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said
here today the United States and China are stepping up cooperation
to nurture China's real estate market.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to a family which has bought their own home
and the neighborhood they live in, Clinton said the U.S. and China
are creating a joint residential building counsel to promote new
technology that is needed for a better and more spacious living
environment for Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the U.S. Ministry of Commerce has been
discussing with related Chinese government agencies the matter on
offering mortgage management expertise to China.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, a Chinese economic and financial hub, is one of the
first in China to reform its housing system. Since 1993, nearly
one third of its local households have purchased their homes with
bank loans, mortgages or through local public housing schemes.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation in this respect focuses on "how to finance people
to buy home from strengthening property rights to developing the
mortgage market," according to the president. 
