<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Cloning Bill Passes First Reading in Knesset </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Knesset (Parliament) has
passed the first reading of a bill that would prohibit genetic
cloning in Israel and impose a punishment of up to three years in
prison for violating the law, local newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which cleared its first reading in the Knesset
Science Committee Tuesday, states that "authorization shall not be
granted to any drug, radiation, or chemical, biological,
radiological or pharmacologic material that ... is intended to
affect the health, body or mental state of a person or a fetus or
any part (of either), including genetic material."
</P>
<P>
Labor Knesset member Haggai Merom, who introduced the bill in
the wake of the successful cloning by Scottish scientists of the
sheep named Dolly early last year, said he was motivated to submit
the bill by growing fears of the possibility of cloning human
beings.
</P>
<P>
Some of the scientists who participated in Tuesday's committee
meeting expressed concern that the legislature has the power to
restrict scientific freedom. But the newspapers quoted Merom as
emphasizing that he had spent much time listening to many
scientists who were invited to help formulate the draft law.
</P>
<P>
"I am optimistic that the wording of the bill provides a
response to the threat while enabling scientists to continue with
their work," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
