<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Better Life For Tibetans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lhasa, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Zhabsang, a 57-year-old Tibetan
woman, who moved out of her low cramped house with her sister and
nephew into a bright three-room flat equipped with telephone and
gas stove, says, "I never imagined that I could live in such
comfort."
</P>
<P>
This is Zhabsang's third move. Before 1959, her parents were
servants of a local landlord at a time when eight family members
were crowded into a dark nine-square-meter room on Bargor Street.
</P>
<P>
But, when compared with those people sleeping out in the open,
even that was considered lucky, she says bitterly. Local archives
showed that, in 1950, those people without their own housing
accounted for 90 percent of the people.
</P>
<P>
After the 1959 democratic reforms in Tibet, Zhabsang's big
family was given three single-storey dwellings that were dark.
</P>
<P>
But, things are changing now, according to Pasang, of Lhasa's
housing bureau. In the past five years, Tibet has spent 1.77
billion yuan (213 million U.S. dollars) on housing. Lhasa tore
down 208,400 square meters of old buildings and helped more than
4,000 families move to new apartments equipped with running water.
</P>
<P>
Urban per capita floor space has been 14 square meters in Tibet
since the 1990s, which is more than the amount of many developed
coastal cities, Pasang says.
</P>
<P>
Today's Lhasa has 51 square kilometers of downtown area, with a
population of 130,000, as opposed to only 3 square kilometers and
30,000 people half a century ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
