<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Wooden Boat Discovered In Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered a vessel that was built more than 870 years ago at the
Cangzhou section of the Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal in Hebei
Province.
</P>
<P>
The 15-meter boat was found while the navigation channel of the
canal was being dredged. The timbers have not rotted even though
it has been submerged for more than 870 years.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists have concluded that the ship is from the Song
Dynasty (960-1127) because of its design and the relics found with
it, like pottery, iron and bronze tools, and coins used during the
Song.
</P>
<P>
The 1,789 kilometer-long Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal was built
during the Sui Dynasty (518-618) and was expanded during the Tang
(618-907) and Song (960-1279). The canal is the world's longest
and serves as a major water course connecting northern and
southern China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Province Plans To Use World Bank Loans For Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- An agricultural resources
development project on the Anning River watershed, in southwest
China's Sichuan Province, is being appraised by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The 2.4-billion-yuan (290 million US dollars) project, with 130
million U.S. dollars from the World Bank, will be decided on by
the bank in December.
</P>
<P>
The Anning is a tributary of the Yangtze, on the upper reaches,
and covers a 3.4 million-hectare area.
</P>
<P>
The project was listed last year as a state-level experiment in
comprehensive agricultural development, mainly focusing on using
biological resources.
</P>
<P>
It will involve 15 counties and 3.4 million people with its
projects in water conservation, grain and fruit production, and
farm product processing. It also aims to help 500,000 needy
farmers, and relocate 400,000 rural laborers.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the province had used World Bank loans
worth 2.1 billion U.S. dollars in 32 projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
