<HEADLINE> Tehran Radio: U.S. Wants to Keep Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran's state-run Tehran radio said
Wednesday that the United States intended to stand in the way of
lifting the U.N. sanctions on Iraq by creating new tension in the
region.
</P>
<P>
In a first reaction to the U.S. missile attack on an Iraqi
radar station on Tuesday, Tehran radio said that the attack was
aimed at postponing the lift of sanctions, imposed after Iraq
invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The attack, taking place after Iraq and the chief U.N. arms
inspector Richard Butler reached an agreement to try to finish the
U.N. arms inspections in Iraq within two months, dampened the
prospect, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. F-16 fighter fired a missile at an Iraqi radar station
Tuesday, on the excuse that the radar locked on four British
patrol planes enforcing the no-fly zone in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The zone was imposed by the U.S., British and French forces in
1991 with the claimed aim to protect Shiite Muslim Iraqis. An
extension of the zone in 1996 pushed its northern boundary to the
33rd parallel.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq said that the radar unit was not working at the
time when it was raided, and it reserved the right to defend.
</P>
<P>
There is so far no official Iranian comment on the attack.
Tehran radio said the latest attack caused great concern about
tension in the region, and called on Baghdad to show
self-restraint in order to prevent a new crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
