<HEADLINE> Museveni Orders Probe Over Senior Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
was so angry with the alleged smuggling activities of senior army
officers that he has ordered an investigation into the issue.
</P>
<P>
Col. Geoffrey Taban, the commanding officer of the Third
Division, and his second-in-command Lt. Col. Levi Karuhanga were
said to have been involved in a case of smuggling goods from
neighboring Kenya, Wednesday's Monitor paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Their trouble began when a Tata lorry of the Uganda People's
Defense Forces (UPDF) was impounded transporting smuggled goods
at a Uganda Revenue Authority (URA) check point in east Mbale
district on June 15, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Taban had allegedly gone to the check point dressed in
civilian attire to negotiate the release of the smuggled goods,
and the lorry from URA customs officials, it added.
</P>
<P>
The impounded goods include 121 cartons and 18 packets of
Kenya-made Supermatch cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
The Commissioner-General of URA, Elly Rwakakooko, said
investigations are being conducted into the matter, adding that
the authority does not accuse anybody until it has proved with
solid evidence that someone had a hand in the smuggling scandal.
</P>
