<HEADLINE> PLA Troops Win Praise of Hong Kong Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The People's Liberation Army (PLA)
troops that have been stationed in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) as of July 1 last year have won praise
from the SAR government and the local people.
</P>
<P>
Liu Zhenwu, commander of the PLA Hong Kong Garrison, said that
his troops are responsible for defending the "one country, two
systems" policy and to see that it strictly follows the law.
</P>
<P>
The PLA Garrison Law exempts servicemen from customs
inspections while on duty, but they follow strict rules and pass a
security check and examine all vehicles and men, whether on duty
or on holiday. No discipline problems have been reported, even
though several thousand officers, enlisted men, and vehicles have
been checked.
</P>
<P>
All officers and enlisted men have two books: the Basic Law and
the Garrison Law. They are required to be familiar with each
article of the two laws, and to act in accordance with them.
</P>
<P>
Because of their rigorous adherence to this, the PLA troops
have impressed many Hong Kong residents. Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the HKSAR, said on the eve of the Traditional Spring
Festival in early this year that with such disciplined troops
responsible for the defence of Hong Kong, the central government,
the SAR government and its people can all rest assured.  
</P>
</TEXT>
