<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electronic Mapping System for S. Africa's 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has spent
millions of U.S. Dollars preparing an electronic mapping system
to position 12,000 voting districts around the country for the
general election next year.
</P>
<P>
The system was jointly compiled by the Independent Electoral
Commission (IEC), the Land Affairs Department, the Central
Statistical Service and hundreds of outside contractors.
</P>
<P>
The system, a computerized geographic and population database,
constitutes the first comprehensive electronic map of every town,
informal settlement, agricultural area and rural village in South
Africa, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
IEC deputy chief electoral officer Norman du Plessis said the
country had been divided into 12,000 voting districts on a
political basis and the size of each district would be determined
by the walking distances to its polling station -- 7.5 kilometers
in urban areas and 10 kilometers in rural regions.
</P>
<P>
Urban voting districts would be limited to a population of
3,000, and those in rural areas to 1,200 people.
</P>
<P>
The delimitation process should be completed by the end of
July.
</P>
<P>
Chief electoral officer Mandla Mchunu said the districts would
be the framework upon which the national common voters' roll
would be compiled. Eligible voters would have to register and
vote in the voting district they live in. The registration of
voters was scheduled to start in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
At the launch of the geographical information system Tuesday,
Australian consultant Jim Howell said the IEC had to use
guesswork in 1994 to estimate the number and places to position
polling stations because it was impossible to determine
population densities over the entire country.
</P>
<P>
"There had never been a formal census population count across
the whole nation, no national voters' roll, and there was no
homogeneous map of the country that would permit election
planning to be performed," Howell said.
</P>
<P>
He added the system is already acknowledged by international
experts as one that could be exported to other countries.
</P>
<P>
South Africa had achieved in 15 months what it took the U.S.
six years to do, said Howell.
</P>
<P>
Du Plessis said the system had a host of wider applications
and could be used effectively to determine the country's
development needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China Province Spending On Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- China's Sichuan Province spent 44.8
billion yuan (5.4 billion US dollars) on infrastructure like water
conservation, transport, communications, and power projects in the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
Zou Guangyan, Sichuan's deputy governor, said that his province
had 78 major infrastructure projects, costing 148.3 billion yuan
(17.9 billion US dollars) from 1996 to 1997. By the end of last
year, 13 key projects were in operation.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan increased water conservation work, adding 62,000
hectares of irrigated area, contributing tremendouly to easing
drought problems in the eastern part of the province.
</P>
<P>
Zou noted that the opening of the 340-km Dacheng Railway in
December last year brought railway service to central and eastern
parts of the province. Highways also got a boost with the
Chengdu-Mianyang and Neijiang-Yibin expressways.
</P>
<P>
Post and telecommunications services were also improved with
the addition of 5,400 km long-distance optical cable, 567 km of
microwave trunk lines, and 105,000 long-distance telephone
terminals.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Sichuan also succeeded in building power plants with
a technology improvement project at the Baima Power Plant and
three 175,000-kw units at the Baozhusi hydro-electric power plant
bringing the total installed generating capacity in Sichuan to
11.1 million kw, Zou said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
