<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Set to Hold Quyi Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- China will host a Quyi Festival
featuring various genre of folk art in Hohhot, capital of the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, from July 10-16.
</P>
<P>
Quyi, a popular entertainment genre consisting mainly of
ballads, storytelling, comic dialogues and clapper talks,
developed from oral presentations of folk stories and songs
popular with various ethnic groups in ancient China.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 300 forms of Quyi, including flourishing
genre such as comic dialogues and storytelling. However,
difficulties remain in developing various forms of the art, with a
number of forms facing the threat of extinction due to challenges
from modern forms of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the festival is to promote the reform and
development of traditional art forms. The organizing committee
reported that the event will attract more than 200 Chinese
artists, as well as artists from the United States, Canada, Hong
Kong and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The festival will also feature various symposia and academic
exchanges to promote the development of Quyi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Insurance Industry Provides On-Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has became the first
Asian country to get its insurance industry
electronically-connected through the Central Administration Bureau
(CAB) for its facultative reinsurance business.
</P>
<P>
A total of 58 insurance and reinsurance companies based in the
country have gone on-line since Wednesday morning, a statement
issued by CAB said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The CAB will handle all administration and central settlement
of the facultative reinsurance business and offers benefits in the
form of increased productivity, faster settlements, reduced
operating costs and improved quality services, it said.
</P>
<P>
The CAB system was an achievement in information technology
which Director of the General Insurance Regulation Department at
Bank Negara (State Bank) Muhammad Ibrahim said could dramatically
change the way the insurance business is conducted in the country.
</P>
<P>
The insurance industry is now looking at a borderless
reinsurance market that is accessible from the office, with CAB
operating as a clearing house for regional insurance exchange, the
official said at the official launching of the CAB system here
Tuesday, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
He called on the industry to explore the possibility of
expanding the scope of the CAB system to include the electronic
settlement of other faculties such as treaty business and
knock-for-knock motor claims.
</P>
<P>
The CAB network can also be utilized to establish a system for
verification of "No Claim Bonus" among insurers, and for the
distribution of circulars to the industry and submissions of
statistics to the General Insurance Association of Malaysia, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The CAB is being developed in two phases, with phase one to
take on the function of actual placement of reinsurance and phase
two to extend its services to handle electronic placements and
acceptances.
</P>
<P>
It will also build up historic data on risks to serve as aid
for underwriting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Using Cheaper Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Gasified straw fuel is being seen
as an environmentally friendly and cheap source of energy in
China's rural area.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in China's Shandong Province held by the Ministry
of Science and Technology, the Ministry of Agriculture, and the
State Bureau of Environmental Protection, participants explained
that gasified straw fuel can avoid waste and pollution.
</P>
<P>
Straw has long been burnt as fuel in rural China, which
produces 600 million tons of straw every year, 200 million tons of
which is used for cooking fires.
</P>
<P>
And, in some of the more developed parts of the countryside
where gas is becoming more popular as fuel, straw that is left in
the field is just burnt on the spot, with 100 million tons going
up in smoke every year.
</P>
<P>
Black smoke produced in this way in Chengdu, the capital of
Sichuan Province caused 61 flights at Shuangliu Airport to be
suspended or cancelled in May, the most man-made cause of flight
delays in China.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the state environmental protection department has
decided to encourage the use of straw gas. According to one
estimate, a million tons of dust and 600,000 tons of sulphur
dioxide could be eliminated if a tenth of China's villages were to
burn straw gas instead of coal.
</P>
<P>
A straw gasification plant consumes 200 tons of straw and
generates 400,000 cu.m. of gas fuel a year, which is equivalent to
the energy produced by 192 tons of coal or 36 tons of LPG. The gas
costs a household 33.9 yuan a month, which is nearly as cheap as
coal and 40 percent less than LPG.
</P>
<P>
A recent Shandong study showed that 75 percent of the farmers
surveyed preferred straw gas, and the province has set up 54
gasification facilities, which help 8,000 households. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
