<HEADLINE> US Helps Train Ugandan Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 34 Ugandan police
officers Tuesday began receiving training by four visiting police
trainers from Los Angeles, the United States.
</P>
<P>
The three-day leadership seminar is aimed at improving the
police's capacity to deliver, the Monitor daily said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chris Bakiza, the director of the Criminal Investigation
Department, said, "It is no longer enough to know the land and
police procedures. We must learn how to lead the rest of our
personnel to rise up to the challenges of a tough job."
</P>
<P>
"There is no way we can any more lose sight of the modern
trends in quality leadership, especially given the challenging
nature of public demands," he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Uganda Nancy Powell said cooperation
between police in both countries should be encouraged because it
is necessary.
</P>
<P>
She hoped the strict training will help improve the image of
the police in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
The delegation of U.S. trainers, led by Prof. Norma Barber
from the Police Department in Los Angeles, includes his wife, Del
Walinga, Sheriff of Orange City Iowa, and Jerry Powell, a trainer
in the Los Angeles Police College. 
</P>
