<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Import Declaration Fee Scrapped in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- From midnight of June 30 on, the
five percent import declaration fee (IDF) has been scrapped on
goods coming into Zambia but importers will be expected to
complete the IDF forms for inspection purposes only.
</P>
<P>
The IDF was a levy on all imports, including vehicles, with a
value of 500 U.S. Dollars or more. It was calculated at the rate
of five percent of cost, insurance and freight value of imports,
Zambia Daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mark Odonnel, chairman of Zambia Association of Manufacturers,
said manufacturers have been waiting for the IDF to be scrapped.
"We now foresee a stabilization and drop in the prices for goods
in shops."
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers will now be more competitive as raw materials
will cost less, he said, adding that Zambians will join the
export arena on a stronger point.
</P>
<P>
The IDF complete cancellation was projected in the 1998 budget
and among other innovations in the budget were the rejected
increment of the minimum duty on second-hand clothes from 1.50 to
five Dollars a kilogram, reduction of duty on a number of raw
materials and the increase of duty on second-hand vehicles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
