<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Says UN Ready to Help Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan has said that the U.N. and the international community
is ready to help Nigeria in its transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived in Nigeria Monday for a four-day visit,
made the remarks Tuesday in Nigerian capital Abuja, at a dinner
hosted in his honor by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, according
to reports reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Annan said his mission in Nigeria is to explore avenues where
the U.N. and the international community could assist Nigeria in
its reconciliation and democratization efforts.
</P>
<P>
He told his host that the U.N. has "no magic formula and we
have not come to dictate, but to offer assistance, if need be."
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said he is encouraged by what the new
leadership of Nigeria under General Abdulsalam Abubakar has done
in a very short period, meaning mainly the release of 26
political detainees.
</P>
<P>
Annan said Nigeria has a key role to play in Africa and the
world at large, for which it should first get its house in order.
</P>
<P>
"There is a great potential in this country, a country with
very talented people, some here, many outside, but the planes fly
both ways, they can come back and help reconstruct," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. chief, it is a consensus that the new
leadership should move ahead to establish a democratic
government.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is this desire to go through a peaceful,
democratic, credible transition that every Nigerian wants and it
is shared and supported by the international community," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
