<HEADLINE> Language Laboratory to Be Set up in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The first ever Language Laboratory
in Sri Lanka, now under construction by the Department of Official
Languages will be soon opened, sources of Official Languages
Commission here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The major objective in establishing this laboratory is to
provide advanced training to Sri Lankan translators and develop
language skills among the public, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first language laboratory to be established in the
South Asian region and it is expected to produce 100 translators
annually.
</P>
<P>
Steps would also be taken to develop the laboratory as a
language Center for the South Asian region by obtaining
international recognition, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government has granted about 10,000 U.S. dollars
for the establishment of the laboratory. The five-storey
laboratory will consist of Sinhala, Tamil, Sanskrit, Arabic and
Pali books. a foreign language section will also be included.
</P>
<P>
The government typists and stenographers will be able to get
computer training at this language center. The language laboratory
is a prime need to develop the language skills of public officers
and the general public, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
