<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines May Import More Rice, Corn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has been
advised to import 700,000 tons of rice and 300,000 tons of corn in
the third quarter of 1998 to have a safer buffer by end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency reported Wednesday that this will
bring total rice and corn imports in 1998 to 1.77 million tons and
1.15 million tons, which are estimated to cost 680 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Economist Rolando Dy as saying that domestic
production of rice is projected this year to decline by at least
12 percent compared to 1997's, similar to that of 1993 when the El
Nino hit the country.
</P>
<P>
"Rice imports of 1.06 million tons during the first half of
1998 is not sufficient because of the one-month delay in the
harvest. Theoretically, harvest would be (starting in) late
September," Dy said.
</P>
<P>
The projected 700,000 tons of rice imports in the next three
months are intended for the one-month delay in the harvest
assuming a minimum of 22,000 tons of daily consumption, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dy said the government must also import 300,000 tons of corn in
the third quarter to solve the expected supply problem because of
delayed planting harvest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
