<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, U.S. Conclude IPR Action Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A press release from the U.S. Embassy in Thailand said
Wednesday that the commitments contained in this agreement will
reinforce efforts by Thailand to raise the level of IPR protection
in the country, and will further strengthen Thailand's legal and
enforcement regimes for IPR once the plan is fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
Specific commitments contained in the Action Plan include the
following: progress toward enactment of world-class patent and
trademark laws; establishment of a permanent inter-agency
committee to coordinate IPR enforcement and the prosecution of
infringers; and development of more effective procedures for
enforcement activity.
</P>
<P>
In conjunction with the announcement of the Action Plan, the
United States will restore to Thailand certain benefits under the
Generalized System of Preferences (GSP) which were revoked for IPR
reasons, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The United States will closely monitor the implementation of
the Action Plan by the Thai government and will continue to
consult with the U.S. business community on the general level of
IPR protection and enforcement in Thailand. Failure to adhere to
or implement these commitments could result in the suspension of
GSP benefits for Thailand, or other actions consistent with the
U.S. trade law, according to the release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
