<HEADLINE> U.S. Players Show Sympathy to Resigned Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Four members of the U.S. World
Cup soccer team showed their sympathy Tuesday to their ex-coach
Steve Sampson, who resigned yesterday after the team wound up the
last among 32 teams in France.
</P>
<P>
Several veteran players of the U.S. team had blamed Sampson for
his poor strategy in the games as well as leaving them on bench.
</P>
<P>
But Brian McBride, who scored the U.S. team's lone goal in the
tournament, said: "I look at it as a whole. It was everybody's
fault, not one person."
</P>
<P>
Sampson, the first American-born coach of a U.S. World Cup
team, was forced out Monday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the team's veteran players were angered by a lack of
playing time and called for his dismissal in the wake of the
team's last-place finish.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. team lost 2-0 to Germany, 2-1 to Iran, and 1-0 to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Juergen Sommer, a member of the 1994 U.S. World Cup team who
was a backup goalkeeper this time, said:"The little mistakes are
what cost us dearly."
</P>
<P>
Forward Eric Wynalda, midfielder Tab Ramos and defender Alexi
Lalas and Jeff Agoos have criticized Sampon's strategy, handling
of personnel and player rotation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
