<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Brunei Strives to Diversify Economy (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Metali called human resources central to the successful
transformation of Brunei into a diversified industrial economy.
The main areas of interest in human resources development are
managerial and industrial skills, with particular emphasis on
entrepreneurial skills as well as vocational and technical
training, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that currently, local expertise and resources in
training and development are limited. "There are only four
vocational schools to train our future workers and a resources
center to retrain our new entrepreneurs," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore we are inviting people from overseas to train
existing entrepreneurs in the managerial skills, in how to be more
commercialized and how to be more globalized in their operations,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that for the diversification of its economic
activities, Brunei opened its doors to foreign investors who can
participate in the above-mentioned four sectors to help transform
its economic landscape.
</P>
<P>
"We consider foreign investment and participation as pivotal
factors in the success of Brunei's aim of diversifying its
economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign investors, the government has introduced
various incentive programs and foreign investors can enjoy among
other benefits tax incentives and pioneer status; excellent
transport and communications infrastructure; and flexible labor
policy.
</P>
<P>
On the effects of the current regional financial crisis on
Brunei's economy, the official said Brunei, like Singapore, is not
seriously affected. "We do not have that kind of serious effect
like Thailand and Indonesia experienced. But because of the
economic situation around us, we have to be a little bit prudent
in our spending. We are very careful about our spending. In fact
our development spending is also being scaled down so that we do
not fall into the trap like other countries in the region," he
said.
</P>
<P>
So Brunei is very careful about this year's development
projects, especially new ones. "We are reducing new projects, but
those on-going ones are still going," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that if other countries in the region show good
improvements, Brunei is bound to be sharing those good things.
</P>
<P>
Supported by an open economic policy and pursuit of liberal
trade at regional and global fora, Brunei aims to become a service
hub for trade and tourism and is moving forward in that direction
by improving its sea ports, airport and telecommunications system.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
