<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Chinese Law For Wildlife Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- An new law on protection of
wildlife in east China was recently adopted by the Standing
Committee of the Ninth People's Congress of Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The law, which takes effect October 1st, is intended to protect
rare and endangered animals and the province's environment.
</P>
<P>
It specifies that wildlife belongs to the state and that local
government should draw up plans for the reasonable use of wildlife
resources.
</P>
<P>
The cost of protecting and managing wildlife by the government
at or above the county level should be part of their budgets, it
says.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it sets April aside as the month to publicize
wildlife protection in the province and the period of April 10 to
April 16 as "Loving Birds Week" for Zhejiang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
