<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Crossing Yarlung Zangbo Gorge By Balloon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese scientists and
adventurers plan to cross the world's longest, deepest and perhaps
the most dangerous gorge on the Yarlung Zangbo River by balloon.
</P>
<P>
The 496-km gorge in Tibet has an average depth of 5,000 meters,
and is a challenge to any adventurer. Several Chinese and foreign
teams had tried to go through it, but have all failed, or in some
cases, been killed.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yong, head of the new team, says that there is not enough
information about the dangerous section of the river, so they
decided that it would be best to see the whole gorge from in the
air first, then use a boat team later. The balloons will help
obtain scientific data about the environment and geographic
conditions, he explains, and can be used in rescue operations in
an area where few people live.
</P>
<P>
Yang is an environmentalist who was a member of a Yangtze River
expedition in 1986, in which 11 people were killed in the floating.
</P>
<P>
For the past decade, floating China's big rivers has become a
popular sport for people who want to test their courage.
</P>
<P>
The Yarlung Zangbo starts on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, the
highest river in the world, and has a lot of rapids and shoals.
</P>
<P>
Yang's 30-member team was selected from hundreds of volunteers
nationwide, and is being supported by Tibet autonomous regional
government. They will head for the gorge this autumn.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
