<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Earliest Example Of The Hundred "Longevity" Characters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- An inscription of a hundred of the
Chinese character "shou", for 'longevity', dating back 770 years
has been discovered in a cave near Guilin, the popular scenic city
in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say that the carving is the oldest design of its kind
to have been discovered in China. In ancient China, the design was
a popular way to celebrate birthdays.
</P>
<P>
The carving was found in a cave 69 km from Guilin. It consists
of 100 characters that measure 178 cm by 148 cm.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that in 1229, Shi Wei, the local
magistrate, wrote the original larger character and it is reported
that the smaller characters were written by 100 local people who
were at least 100 years old. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
