<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, July 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA -- Bangladesh's Jatiya Sangsad, the country's parliament,
passed the Finance Bill 1998 for the 1998-99 fiscal year
beginning July 1, press reports here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Bill, to come into effect on July 1, was adopted
after Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria declared amendments to
the tax measures proposed in the new budget, including the
withdrawal or reduction of taxes, duties and value-added taxes on
16 items. (Bangladesh-Budget)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Hong Kong, a small region of less than 1,100
square kilometers inhabited by over six million people, has
developed into an economic powerhouse despite its lack of natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong economy has nearly quadrupled over the past two
decades, with its GDP growing at an average annual rate of about
seven percent in real terms. The World Bank has ranked Hong Kong's
 per capita GDP, in terms of purchasing power parity, the sixth
highest in the world. (Hong Kong-Economy Backgrounder)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The Kenyan government's current account improved
from a deficit of 93 million U.S. Dollars in the year ending April
1997 to a deficit of 39 million Dollars in the year ending April
1998, the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) said.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in the current account is attributed to the
services account surplus which rose by 952 million Dollars due to
the reduction in interest rate payments by 97 million Dollars,
Tuesday's East African Standard quoted latest CBK data as saying.
(Kenya-Deficit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Africa's economy expanded by 3.7 percent last year,
lower than the growth rate of five percent in the previous year, a
survey reaching here says.
</P>
<P>
However, economies in certain African countries grew faster,
the East African Standard newspaper Tuesday quoted the survey as
reporting. (African Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA -- Malawi beleaguered economy could get some help from
rising world tea prices resulting from decreased production of
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Currently Malawi tea can fetch 1.48 U.S. Dollars per kilogram
compared to 0.99 Dollars in 1997 and 1996. (Malawi-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- House prices in Britain rose by an average of 11.3
percent in the year to June, down from an annual rate of increase
of 11.9 percent in May, Nationwide, Britain's largest building
society said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of property transactions in May totalled just
108,000, the lowest figure in nearly three years.  (UK-Home
Prices)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUDAPEST -- The Hungarian economy appeared slightly healthier
in the first quarter with its gross national product (GNP) rising
by 4.9 percent over the same period last year, the Central Bureau
of Statistics (CBS) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the three-month period, Hungarian industry grew by 12
percent, construction by 17.2 percent, transportation and post and
telecommunications 6.3 percent, with agriculture and fishery down
7.9 percent. (Hungary-Economy) 
</P>
</TEXT>
