<HEADLINE> Interview: Brunei Strives to Diversify Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANDER SERI BEGAWAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Brunei, always
associated with lucrative oil and gas industries, has been making
great efforts to diversify its economy by developing non-oil and
-gas industries and has been reaping the benefit.
</P>
<P>
"Brunei is on the track of diversifying its economy. We are
looking into non-oil sectors now," Metali Bin Haji Damit, head of
the Industry Promotion Unit of the Ministry of Industry and
Primary Resources, told Xinhua in a recent exclusive interview
here.
</P>
<P>
Toward this end, Brunei's seventh National Development Plan
(NDP) (1996-2000) is aimed at diversifying the economy, he said,
adding that with a budget allocation of 7.2 billion Brunei dollars
(about 5 billion U.S. dollars), it focuses on the development of
infrastructure and social and human resources as a basis for
industrial growth.
</P>
<P>
And to supplement the NDP, the government endorsed a five-year
Industrial Development Plan (IDP) two years ago, which mainly aims
at promoting growth of the private sector for a wider economic
base and a number of sectors have been identified for fast track
implementation, Metali said.
</P>
<P>
"Under the IDP, which shares 12.6 percent of the total budget
allocation, we are encouraging and promoting four sectors --
primary resources sector which includes agriculture, fisheries and
forestry; manufacturing; services industries, especially tourism;
and human resources development to complement the existing
contributions of oil and gas," he said.
</P>
<P>
Brunei is an oil-rich sultanate, located right in the heart of
Southeast Asia, with a land mass of 5,765 square kilometers and a
population of 314,400. In its economy, the oil and gas industries
have long been the dominant sector, accounting for more than 50
percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Since the Brunei government's move to promote non-oil and -gas
activities, some promising results have been shown with the
non-oil and -gas sector taking a bigger share in the GDP, Metali
said.
</P>
<P>
The non-oil sector grew at an average rate of 5.7 percent per
annum during the sixth NDP period (1991-1995), with its
contribution to the gross domestic product (GDP) at current prices
increasing from 46.4 percent in 1990 to 64.1 percent in 1995, and
the non-oil and
-gas sector in 1997 grew further to take up about 64.4 percent of
the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Brunei has enjoyed a steady economic growth in the past few
years with its real GDP growth rate in 1997 standing at 4 percent
against 3.5 percent in 1996 and 3 percent in 1995, according to
the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
