<HEADLINE> Antique Smugglers Detained in Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Two Bulgarian smugglers have been
detained, with antiques worth 70,000 Deutsche marks (124,600
U.S. dollars) seized, the Interior Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Z. Georgiev, 36, the mastermind of the smuggling, and his wife
B. Ivanov, 47, were detained when they were trying to leave the
country through the Vrushka Chouka border checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
A total of 33 Roman silver and bronze coins, statuettes and
collages of exceptional historic value were found stashed in a
secret compartment behind the upholstery of Georgiev's vehicle.
</P>
<P>
In Georgiev's house, a bronze statuette of Venus and several
masks of Oriental deities were discovered. Other valuable antiques
seized were 597 antique coins, four statuettes, jewelry and icons.
</P>
<P>
Both Georgiev and his wife are from Montana, northwestern
Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
They have been under surveillance for several months by
Bulgarian anti-mafia services, who had discovered an international
smuggling route via Bulgaria to Yugoslavia and then to Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
