<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manufacturing Output Rises in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Increases posted by 12 out of 16
major sectors pulled up the manufacturing sector's overall value
of production (VPI) in the Philippines by 7.2 percent during the
first quarter of 1998 from the 1997 level.
</P>
<P>
According to a National Statistics Office survey published here
Wednesday, value and volume of net sales rose by 5.7 and 4.2
percent respectively over last year, spurred mainly by wearing
apparel.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that the year-on-year VPI was led by
electrical machinery with a growth of 48.9 percent due to gains in
micro-circuits and electrical appliances.
</P>
<P>
It was followed by chemicals with an increase of 25.8 percent,
food 10.7 percent, wearing apparel 34.2 percent, and paper and
paper products 34.8 percent, the survey says.
</P>
<P>
It also indicates that basic metals and transport equipment, on
the other hand, dropped by 22.2 and 35.3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
On a month-on-month basis, the survey says, the VPI moved up by
1.2 percent in March as food registered an increase of 10.6
percent, contributing significantly to the overall performance.
</P>
<P>
Sectors that posted significant increases were chemicals, 6
percent; non-metallic mineral products, 12 percent; electrical
machinery, 2.9 percent; beverage, 13.2 percent; and paper and
paper products, 5.7 percent, it says.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that losers include basic metals, which
declined by 22.3 percent, and wearing apparel, which declined by
9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey also says the volume of production index (VoPI) for
manufacturing of 145.8 during the three-month period represented a
decline of 1.7 percent from last year's.
</P>
<P>
On a month-on-month basis, the VoPI went up by 3.7 percent in
March largely due to the 10.5-percent increase in food
manufacturing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
