<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freeze-Dried Sperm Works to Create New Mice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Scientists from the U.S.
University of Hawaii have demonstrated that mouse sperm can be
freeze-dried and then used to create mice by adding water, the
Washington Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Hawaii scientists first got the mouse sperm freeze-dried
and stored them at room temperature for three months. Finally
they added water with the sperm and injected then into mouse eggs,
making the eggs fertilized and injected them into surrogate mother
mice. By this way, the surrogate mice gave birth to offsprings.
</P>
<P>
This feat offers graphic evidence for the astonishing
resilience of DNA inside sperm. More practically, it could
simplify long-term storage of semen from laboratory and farm
animals, perhaps even from people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
