<HEADLINE> China Building "Forest" Of Newspaper Steles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- China plans to build a "forest of
steles" that contain newspapers and other publications and has
completed the first one for "People's Daily" to mark the 50th
anniversary of the paper.
</P>
<P>
The "forest" is in the central part of Fenghuang (Phoenix)
Mountain in Hubei Province on a planned 18-hectare plot of ground,
which will consist of more than 20,000 steles erected at a cost of
more than 90 million yuan (10.8 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The project was started by Xu Kongzhang, a retired official in
the city of Xianning who has collected newspapers and other
publications for the past 50 years. His collection now has more
than 100,000 copies of various newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
Xu has collected over 8,600 Chinese and overseas newspapers and
magaines. His project has won the support of the All-China
Journalists' Association and the Xianning city government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
