<HEADLINE> Thai Labor Groups Seek Government Help for Jobless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's labor groups Tuesday
asked the government to urgently establish a special welfare fund
for the rehabilitation of the unemployed in order to prevent
possible social unrest, the newspaper The Nation reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The groups, led by Labor Congress of Thailand President
Pratuang Saengsang, proposed that the money for the fund come from
the government's 21.6 billion baht (526 million U.S. dollars)
Social Investment Fund or from other sources without employees,
employers and the government having to contribute to the fund.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Labor and Social Welfare Secretary Phan Chantharapan
was quoted as saying there is a possibility of establishing a
special fund for the unemployed as demanded by the labor groups
since his ministry has about 2 billion baht (48 million dollars)
in loans to solve workers' problems.
</P>
<P>
More than 2 million workers in Thailand have lost their jobs
since the economic crisis started last year, according to the Thai
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
