<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: New Philippine Government Challenged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Joseph Estrada has assumed office as
the president of the Philippines and analysts here said the
severest test facing his administration is to revive the economy,
which has been plagued by the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Estrada does not see this as a good time for him to assume the
presidency as the country's economy has been badly battered by the
crisis. But he expressed confidence that with the help of the
business community and his countrymen as a whole, he would be able
to lead the country out of the current economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
One year after the financial crisis started, its full impacts
have become apparent in the Philippines. Data released by the
National Statistics Office show that in the first quarter, growth
of the gross national product (GNP) slowed down to 2.5 percent
while that of the gross domestic product (GDP) slid to 1.7
percent, 2.9 and 3.4 percentage points lower when compared with
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
GDP, a measure of economic output, covers both goods and
services produced in a country while GNP includes GDP and incomes
from overseas.
</P>
<P>
The poor performance of the agricultural and industrial sectors
has been blamed as the main reason for the economic slump as both
sectors bore the brunt of peso depreciation, runaway interest
rates, tight credit and severe drought caused by El Nino. During
the period, the agricultural sector contracted by 3.6 percent
while industry grew by a mere 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Investments and exports, two engines for the economy, have also
slowed down. In the first three months, investments dropped by 7.4
percent, a sharp reversal from the 14.9-percent expansion in the
same period last year. Exports went up by 11.6 percent, lower than
the 22.3 percent recorded last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inflation and jobless rates have also surged to a
high that the country had not seen for years. In April, inflation
rose to 10.3 percent due to soaring prices while the unemployment
rate jumped to 13.3 percent with 4.3 million people left without
job.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter, the country's fiscal picture was also
not as good as expected. Its gross international reserve increased
to 11 billion U.S. dollars and the balance of payments showed a
surplus of 2 billion dollars, but the budget deficit and foreign
debts rose as well, to 15.4 billion pesos (370 million dollars)
and 51 billion dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The first-quarter situation does not give us too much room for
optimism," said Shiladitya Chatterjee, a senior economist at the
Asian Development Bank (ADB). He said the Philippines' economic
slump will probably be "more painful" than forecasts made earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine economy is dependent on imports, but in the past
10 months, imports have been declining. Although this helped
reduce the huge trade deficit and current account deficit, it also
hindered the growth of exports, ADB said in an annual report.
</P>
<P>
The bank added that another factor likely to weigh on the
economy is a shortfall of credit and higher interest rates as
banks are facing rising bad loans. As of March, the banking
system's non-performing loans had risen to 8.3 percent of the
total loan portfolio and four small banks had been closed.
</P>
<P>
Chatterjee's forecast was confirmed by the reduction of fleet
size by Philippine Airlines. The company, due to the Asian crisis
and a strike by 620 pilots, tail-spun into the gravest financial
crisis in its history. It was forced to terminate leases on 27
planes ahead of time, sell off 13 aircraft and lay off 5,000
employees. Economists believe that Philippines Airlines is just
the epitome of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the poor first-quarter figures, the government
cut its GNP target for 1998 from 3-4 percent to 2.5 percent,
revising its budget spending from a surplus of 5 billion pesos
(125 million dollars) to a planned deficit of 36.4 billion pesos
(9.1 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The target for GDP remains unchanged, but economists believe
that even the 2.4-3.5 percent growth rate is hard to achieve and
they predict a maximum GDP growth rate of 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bearing in mind that hard times are still ahead, Estrada began
working for the economy after winning the presidential election on
May 11. He held talks with the business sector and won the support
of those who accused him of knowing nothing about economics.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also vowed to continue the economic reforms and
policies of the previous administration, calling on foreign
businessmen to invest more in the country.
</P>
<P>
The new government said it targets an average of 5 percent
growth rate in GDP for the next five years. To achieve this
target, it would give top priority to the development of
agriculture and aim for at least a 3-percent growth in the sector
every year.
</P>
<P>
However, although it may suffer further economic slump, the
Philippines is still in a better position than other economies hit
by the financial crisis. Economists predict that Indonesia, Korea,
Thailand and Malaysia would register negative economic growth this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
