<HEADLINE> Widespread Poverty Revealed in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Poverty has become the biggest
scourge of Ecuador with nearly 60 percent of the population
classified as living under the poverty line in a national survey.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Statistics and Census Institute, 43
percent of the urban population and as many as 85 percent of the
rural population are living in poverty, involving 6.5 million
people in total.
</P>
<P>
The survey puts the nation's homeless rate at 20 percent, or
2.35 million people.
</P>
<P>
The indigenous people are among the hardest hit in Ecuador,
with 74 percent living in poverty and 37 percent homeless.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found 13.8 percent of the working population
jobless and 53.6 percent under-employed, while more than one half
of the nation has no access to general health care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic to Cut Down Military Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic will reduce the
size of its armed forces from 78,000 at present to 60,000 in the
year 2003, as a major step to ease military budget demand.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Michal Lobkowicz told reporters Monday evening
that the reduction would mainly effect office staffs and
commissioned officers.
</P>
<P>
Officers account for 67 percent of the country's total armed
forces, as against an average 26 percent in NATO countries,
Lobkowicz added.
</P>
<P>
The funds saved from the reduction would be mainly used to
upgrade military equipment and improve training facilities, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The budget for the Czech military in 1997 was only 790 million
Korunas (23.9 million U.S. dollars), representing 1.66 percent of
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The percentage was remarkably lower than Poland's 2.28 percent
and Slovakia's 2.18 percent in the same year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Assigns Area for Disaster Prevention Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian government has
assigned an area in the Canal Zone for the establishment of the
Coordination Center for Natural Disaster Prevention in Central
America, the regional interoceanic authority announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the International Agreement for Natural
Disasters Prevention, signed in Panama City last April by Central
American relief organizations.
</P>
<P>
The new installation -- covering 739 square meters -- will be
located in the Curundu plains, an area by the canal, returned by
the United States in 1997 to Panama under the Torrijos-Carter
treaty.
</P>
<P>
The center, a apart of the Central American Integrated System,
will be able to monitor and take preventive steps in case of
natural disasters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
