<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Raises Minimum Wages by 15 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government Tuesday
announced it will increase minimum wages by an average of 15
percent to arrest the decline in real wages caused by soaring
inflation, according to local press reports Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The pay rise will be effective as of August 1 this year for all
companies in all Indonesia's provinces, Manpower Ministry
spokesman Syaufie Syamsuddin was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the government will let companies which are
undergoing financial difficulties as a result of the prolonged
monetary crisis delay paying the increased wages to their workers.
</P>
<P>
Despite the 15-percent increase, this year's new wage will only
amount to 76 percent of the workers' minimum living cost which has
been calculated at 205,000 rupiah (about 20 U.S. dollars) per
month.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government traditionally increases minimum wages
on April 1. This year, the raise was frozen by the then government
of President Soeharto because of the economic crisis, a decision
widely criticized by trade unions.
</P>
<P>
President B.J. Habibie, who replaced Soeharto on May 21, has
made the provision of social safety net programs his chief
priority to help the poor cope with the harsh economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
The government said inflation was running at 56.7 percent in
the first six months of this year. It has predicted that inflation
will reach 80 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Syaufie said the increase was the result of negotiations
involving representatives of the government, employers and
workers, with the final proposals coming from all the provincial
governors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
