<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Nazi Gold to Fund Holocaust Survivors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Tuesday
that most of the remaining gold looted by the Nazis during World
War II has now been returned and that about three quarters of it
will be donated to Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters following a conference on Holocaust-era
assets here, U.S. Under Secretary of State Stuart Eizenstat said
that all claimant countries except Albania and the former Yugoslav
states had now received their shares of the gold.
</P>
<P>
He said three quarters of the gold, whose total value was put
at 41 million U.S. dollars at current rates, had been contributed
by recipient countries to the Holocaust fund.
</P>
<P>
Austria, Greece, Italy and the Netherlands have donated all of
their share to the fund, said the U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
The fate of the six tons of gold, last of 337 tons collected by
Second World War allies, had been left unresolved by a London
conference last December. All the rest had been progressively
handed back to the banks since 1946.
</P>
<P>
"This is, I think, a just close-out of a 50-year effort,"
Eizenstat said. "No further claims can be made once this final
receipt is done."
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat, who chaired the U.S. State Department conference on
Holocaust-era assets, said overall pledges to the fund from
various countries totalled 57.5 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 39 countries participating in the conference also
launched a campaign to identify some 220,000 pieces of art looted
by Nazis from Holocaust victims during the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat told the meeting that the search also will deal with
unpaid life and property insurance claims.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that "the debate over Nazi-confiscated art
often intrudes on questions of sovereignty and the sacred ground
of national heritage."
</P>
<P>
In early June, the Association of Art Museum Directors
recommended that American art museums check their collections to
determine if any works were stolen during the war and to set up a
worldwide database for tracking.
</P>
<P>
The Museum of Modern Art in New York recently stopped
prosecutors from seizing two Egon Schiele paintings on loan from
the Leopold Foundation of Vienna. Two families claim the works
were plundered during the Nazi era from relatives.
</P>
<P>
In May, the Dutch government widened its own investigation into
the ownership of thousands of artworks recovered from Nazis but
never claimed.
</P>
<P>
The 4,000 items ranged from paintings to ceramic objects and
included works by Dutch masters Rembrandt and Van Gogh.
</P>
<P>
During World War II, Nazis also looted insurance policies,
collecting from companies on deaths and property losses. The
amount potentially at stake is incalculable.
</P>
<P>
The German insurance company Allianz is in the midst of a
research program under the direction of Gerald Feldman, a
professor of modern German history at the University of California
at Berkeley, according to press releases from the meeting.
</P>
<P>
A conference will be held in Washington in November to assess
progress on the art and insurance fronts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
