<HEADLINE> Tung: "One Country, Two Systems" Works Out Very Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong leader said here
Wednesday that the principle of "one country, two systems" has
been successfully implemented in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) since the return of Hong Kong one year
ago.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a ceremony marking the first anniversary of Hong
Kong's return to China, Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the SAR,
announced: "The 'one country, two systems' concept worked out
remarkably well in the past year."
</P>
<P>
"Most important of all, the successful implementation of the
'one country, two systems' manifests that the people of Hong Kong
have truly become masters of their own destiny," Tung said at the
celebration gathering at the Hong Kong Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong leader noted that neither the central government
nor any mainland authorities have interfered with the internal
affairs of Hong Kong. On the contrary, the central government has
repeated its pledge to maintain the prosperity and stability of
Hong Kong at all costs when the Asian financial crisis dealt a
severe blow to Hong Kong's economy.
</P>
<P>
"Such an undertaking is a great encouragement to all the people
of Hong Kong," said Tung, who vowed that the SAR government would
live up to people's expectations and make vigorous efforts to help
them ride out of difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government announced bold initiatives in the SAR first
financial budget early this year and recently unveiled a stimulus
package to revive the economy, relieve the people's suffering and
restore confidence in the market.
</P>
<P>
Tung believed that Hong Kong would also benefit a great deal
from the rapid development and prosperity of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
He urged the people of Hong Kong to summon unprecedented
courage to overcome the difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"We will not stand still, nor should we go backwards," the
chief executive said. "The conviction that we made in the glorious
days, i.e. 'the people of Hong Kong can definitely govern Hong
Kong well', will never be shaken by the changes of circumstances."
</P>
</TEXT>
