<HEADLINE> Indonesia Enjoys Trade Surplus in January-April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's trade balance from
January to April 1998 enjoyed a surplus of 7.186 billion U.S.
dollars, an increase of 203 percent over the same period of last
year, a government official said.
</P>
<P>
Sugito Suwito, head of the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS),
said here Tuesday that the country enjoyed the trade surplus due
to sharply declining imports during that period which reached 36.1
percent or 5.133 billion dollars compared with that of the
corresponding period of last year when the figure stood at 14.217
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The decline in imports was caused by trade sluggishness
experienced by the country's business world," official Antara News
Agency Wednesday quoted Sugito as saying.
</P>
<P>
The value of the country's exports from January to April
reached a total of 16.27 billion dollars, a decline of 1.9 percent
compared with the same period in 1997 when the figure was 16.585
billion U.S. dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
Of the total exports, the oil and gas sector contributed 2.785
billion dollars (about 17.12 percent), while the rest were non-oil
and gas commodities which totaled 13.485 billion dollars (about
82.88 percent).
</P>
<P>
The record 80-percent decline of the rupiah (national currency)
since July last year caused massive cutbacks in imports, he said,
adding that rising import costs had hit Indonesia's
export-oriented industries which have had to pay more for raw
materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
