<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria, US Begin Cornerstone '98 Joint Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria and the United States
Tuesday launched their Cornerstone '98 joint humanitarian exercise
in Trun, in the northwest of Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
An engineering unit of the American Army National Guard of
Tennessee and the training engineering unit No. 55 of the
Bulgarian Army are taking part in the exercise.
</P>
<P>
The exercise is a step towards Bulgaria's integration into the
North Atlantic structures, said Lieutenant General Nikola Kolev,
Deputy Chief of General Staff of the Bulgarian Army.
</P>
<P>
Since the exercise is only concerned with the repair of a local
hospital no arms will be used in the joint military campaign, the
general said.
</P>
<P>
"We are working together for friendship between our two
countries," said Colonel William Maccoy, representative of the U.S.
Army.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. servicemen will rotate in three groups of 60 at
intervals of 15 days. A contingent of 27 sergeants and officers
will stay in Trun permanently.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian contingent consists of 62 engineering troops, 26
officers and sergeants stationed permanently and a unit of 130
servicemen providing logistic support.
</P>
<P>
The three Bulgarian platoons which took part in the
peacekeeping mission in Bosnia will also participate in
Cornerstone '98, said Major General Tencho Dobrev, coordinator of
the exercise.
</P>
<P>
"This is not the only project Bulgaria is working on jointly
with the United States," Lieutenant General Nikola Kolev said.
"The country is involved in 30 exercises under the Partnership for
Peace program." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
