<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 39 Nations Vow to Search for Nazis-Looted Art Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States and 38 other
nations launched a campaign on Tuesday to identify some 220,000
pieces of art looted by Nazis from Holocaust victims during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 220,000 pieces of art, about one-quarter in
Europe, were taken from Jews at the start of World War II, said
U.S. Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat, who chaired a day-long conference at the Holocaust
Museum, told the meeting that the search also will deal with
unpaid life and property insurance claims.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat acknowledged that "the debate over Nazi-confiscated
art often intrudes on questions of sovereignty and the sacred
ground of national heritage."
</P>
<P>
But, he said, "We also have a great responsibility to Holocaust
survivors and their heirs" to shed light on these issues.
</P>
<P>
In early June, the Association of Art Museum Directors
recommended that American art museums check their collections to
determine if any works were stolen during the war and to set up a
worldwide database for tracking.
</P>
<P>
The Museum of Modern Art in New York recently stopped
prosecutors from seizing two Egon Schiele paintings on loan from
the Leopold Foundation of Vienna. Two families claimed the works
were plundered during the Nazi era from their relatives.
</P>
<P>
In May, the Dutch government widened its own investigation into
the ownership of thousands of artworks recovered from Nazis but
never claimed. The 4,000 items ranged from paintings to ceramic
objects and included works by Dutch masters Rembrandt and Van Gogh.
</P>
<P>
During World War II, Nazis also looted insurance policies,
collecting from companies on deaths and property losses. The
amount potentially at stake is incalculable.
</P>
<P>
The German insurance company Allianz is in the midst of a
research program under the direction of Gerald Feldman, a
professor of modern German history at the University of California
at Berkeley, according to press releases from the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Research is also under way at the Generali insurance company in
Trieste, Italy. The city was part of the Austro-Hungarian empire
before the war and many Jews who lived in that area placed their
insurance with Generali.
</P>
<P>
A conference will be held in Washington in November to assess
progress on the art and insurance fronts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
