<HEADLINE> Chinese Joint Ventures Provide Jobs For Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIHAI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A 35-year-old man who was unemployed
until just two days ago is now head of a security team of a joint
venture hotel in a Chinese port city.
</P>
<P>
Chen Hua was one of 13 lucky workers who had lost their jobs at
a state enterprise but were recently hired by the hotel in Beihai,
in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shihai, the hotel's general manager, says that they put
ads in local newspapers about openings for unemployed workers
below the age of 35, and 13 applicants passed the exam, and things
have worked out well so far.
</P>
<P>
"We welcomed the state enterprise workers because we believe
they are well-trained and disciplined," Wang says, and explains
that Chen was offered the position of head of the security team
because he had military experience and is a member of the
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the 1,200 enterprises with overseas
investment in the city have already become a major source of jobs
for laid-off workers. The Beihai Tainan Biscuit Co., which is
owned by a Taiwanese businessman, now employs over 200 people, 90
percent of whom were unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Liao Wei, Tainan's general manager, says that he himself was
one of the laid-off workers, but, in 1995, got work with Tainan,
and worked his way up to the present post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
