<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment In Chinese Tourist Spot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Guilin, in south China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, is one of the most famous tourist
attractions in China and now it is attracting foreign investment
as well.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the city had approved 754 overseas-funded
projects worth two billion U.S. dollars, 1.27 billion U.S. dollars
of which was from foreign investors like Pepsi Cola of the United
States, Nokia of Finland, Daewoo of the Republic of Korea, Henkel
of Germany, NEC of Japan, Pilkington of Britain, and Chia Tia of
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"The overseas presence is changing from the traditional tourism
to other sectors like industry, infrastructure, information, and
technology," says Li Zhuozhi, deputy director of the city's
foreign trade and economic cooperation bureau. Guilin has 450,000
international tourists a year.
</P>
<P>
The overseas investment is showing signs of increasing. A
recent three-day trade fair had 55 deals worth 460 million
U.S. dollars, 380 million of that from overseas investors, Li
says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
