<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, July 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Tuesday
expressed concern over the recent violent incidents in East Timor
which have resulted in the death of innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Annan welcomed the atmosphere of greater
openness that has created wider possibilities for a discussion of
the future of East Timor. (UN-Annan-East Timor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO)
Tuesday urged the U.N. Security Council to guarantee the
rescinding of the Israeli plan aimed at putting Jewish settlements
under Jerusalem municipal authority.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian people could not give up Jerusalem," PLO U.N.
Observer Nasser al-Kidwa told a council debate on the question.
</P>
<P>
He said the plan, approved by Israel's cabinet on June 21, will
expand the municipal boundaries of the city and establish an
"umbrella city" to include a number of illegal settlements in the
West Bank. (UN-Israeli-Jerusalem Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States is seeking pledges from the
Albanian separatists in Kosovo to halt their attacks on Serb
civilians and to talk with Belgrade, a senior U.S. official said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The official, who spoke to reporters on condition of anonymity,
said American diplomats have held several secret meetings with
leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army, which had been branded a
terrorist group. (US-Kosovo-Rebels)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi arrived here
Tuesday night, leading Italy as the pioneer of the European
countries in improving relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's visit to Tehran is the first one by a western head of
government since the Islamic revolution in 1979. Both Tehran and
Rome see the visit as an important step for expansion of
Tehran-Rome relations and a further detente between Iran and the
European Union (EU). (Iran-Italy-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- In response to President Ezer Weizman's criticism
on his policy, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Tuesday
stressed that he will not change his stance in the peace
negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with Israel Television, Netanyahu said
that he is struggling for the security of the country and wants to
reach a "good agreement" with the Palestinians. (Israel-PM-Peace
Policy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq Tuesday slammed missile attack by the United
States on a missile site in the southern province of Basra, saying
"it is an aggressive and unjustifiable action."
</P>
<P>
"It is another proof of aggressiveness of the Americans, and it
is a clear evidence of their aggressiveness of the security and
sovereignty of the Iraqi people," the spokesman of the Iraqi
Ministry of Information and Culture said. (Iraq-Missile
Attack-Reaction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said on
Tuesday the United States was firing a missile on Iraq's radar
site to warn Baghdad that it should not intervene with U.S. and
its allies' patrol mission over the no-fly zone in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Cohen was commenting on the missile attack by a U.S. F-16
fighter at an Iraqi surface-to-air missile battery in southern
Iraq early on Tuesday. (US-Iraq-Missile)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
