<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Indian Diversified Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved here
Tuesday financing of a total 130 million U.S. dollars to assist
India's Uttar Pradesh diversified agriculture project.
</P>
<P>
The financing includes an interest-free credit of 50 million
dollars and an 80 million dollar loan from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
This poverty-focused project will accelerate rural development
and benefit poor farmers, especially women, across the state of
Uttar Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
With a population of more than 150 million and an annual per
capita income of 200 dollars, Uttar Pradesh is the most populous
and one of the poorest states in India. Four out of five people in
the state live in the rural areas and about three-quarters of the
state's population depend on agriculture for their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
This project supports the diversification and intensification
of agriculture by introducing new crops and better farming and
animal husbandry practices. The project will also expand farmers'
access to credit and will finance critically-needed investments in
rural roads and markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
