<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Urged to Rescind Israeli Jerusalem Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO) Tuesday urged the U.N. Security Council to
guarantee the rescinding of the Israeli plan aimed at putting
Jewish settlements under Jerusalem municipal authority.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian people could not give up Jerusalem," PLO U.N.
Observer Nasser al-Kidwa told a council debate on the question.
</P>
<P>
He said the plan, approved by Israel's cabinet on June 21, will
expand the municipal boundaries of the city and establish an
"umbrella city" to include a number of illegal settlements in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"That represents a concrete step towards the illegal annexation
of more occupied Palestinian lands to the already illegally
expanded Jerusalem municipality, and towards maintaining a
specific demographic composition with the aim of further
`Judaization' of the city," he said.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the years, Israel has undertaken a number of illegal
and immoral policies and measures to annex occupied territories,
confiscate lands and expand municipal boundaries and to isolate
East Jerusalem from the rest of the West Bank, Kidwa said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli measures are creating a situation that "might lead
to the explosion of the whole region at any moment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kidwa said Palestine hopes that the Security Council will have
the will to finally undertake the necessary measures to guarantee
the rescinding of the plan.
</P>
<P>
Taking the floor at the debate, U.S. Ambassador to the U.N.
Bill Richardson said the U.S. regrets the Israeli announcement.
"That decision is unhelpful at the current stage of negotiations,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"All parties should refrain from any unilateral action which
could prejudge the outcome of the permanent status negotiations,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Russian representative Sergey V. Lavrov said Russia shares the
negative reaction of the international community to the Israeli
plan. "Those Israeli actions further complicate the Middle East
peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the European Union, British
representative John Weston said the Union is deeply concerned by
the Israeli plan as it will alter the demographic balance in the
city area.
</P>
<P>
By initiating, encouraging and endorsing settlement activity in
the occupied territories, the Israeli government is in violation
of the Geneva Convention which applies de facto and de jure to
those territories, he noted.
</P>
<P>
French representative Alan Dejammet said all legislative and
administrative measures taken by Israel that changed the character
and status of Jerusalem are null and void and should be revoked
immediately.
</P>
<P>
Other speakers, numbering close to 40, were actually all
critical of the Israeli plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multiple Births Jump With Fertility Drugs in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Fertility drugs boosted a
record multiple births of 6,000 babies in 1996 in the United
States, a 19 percent increase over the previous year, the
government said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The multiple birth rate has doubled since 1990, quadrupled
since 1980 and is five times higher than it was in 1971, said the
National Center for Health Statistics in its annual report.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there were 100,750 babies born as twins, 5,298 as
triplets, 560 as quadruplets and 81 as quintuplets or other
higher-order multiple births, the report said.
</P>
<P>
About 20 percent of women undergoing fertility therapy have
multiple births in 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, experts warned that although fertility drugs help
thousands of parents to get pregnant, babies from multiple births
are much more likely to be born premature and underweight and
often leads to vision and hearing impairments, mental retardation,
developmental delays and even death.
</P>
<P>
The report said just 6 percent of single births result in low
birthweight babies, but for twins, it's 53 percent; for triplets,
93 percent. Just 8 percent of single births are premature versus
53 percent for twins and 92 percent for triplets.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, 3 percent of babies died in the first month overall,
but for multiple births, it was 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report also found that the number of women smoking while
pregnant dropped, from 20 percent in 1989 to 13.6 percent. But the
number of pregnant teenagers who smoke increased.
</P>
<P>
About 1.2 million children were born to unmarried mothers, or
about one-third of all births. But there was a 1 percent drop in
all out-of-wedlock births.
</P>
<P>
Births to unmarried black women have dropped 18 percent since
1989. A total of 7.4 percent of unmarried black women of
childbearing age gave birth in 1996, the lowest level since the
government began keeping statistics in 1969. The rate for Hispanic
women was 9.3 percent, and for white women, 2.8 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
