<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Seeks Participation of Kosovo Rebels in Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States is seeking
pledges from the Albanian separatists in Kosovo to halt their
attacks on Serb civilians and to talk with Belgrade, a senior U.S.
official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The official, who spoke to reporters on condition of anonymity,
said American diplomats have held several secret meetings with
leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army, which had been branded a
terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
U.S. special envoys Richard Holbrooke and Robert Gelbarde
shuttled last week between Belgrade and Kosovo to seek a
cease-fire between the rebels and the Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
The official indicated that the rebels, who are fighting to
overthrow the Serbs and declare independence, control a great deal
of territory in Kosovo and should be represented in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"They have become a significant political force as a result of
their military power," the official said in outlining the latest
American diplomatic efforts to arrange a cease-fire, and
negotiations between Serbs and ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that there needs to be a "single
negotiating team" under the leadership of Ibrahim Rugova, a more
moderate ethnic Albanian leader who also seeks independence of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"While we obviously accept and support the idea of pluralism in
Kosovo, as everywhere else, there needs to be a common front, and
that is really quite essential for now, and they have to be
willing to accept that," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly want to see them -- we have urged that they
oppose the idea of actions against noncombatants, both Serb and
Albanian and others," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
At least 88,000 Albanians have been made homeless, according to
State Department officials. Of these, 60,000 to 85,000 remain in
Kosovo, 15,000 are in Montenegro and 13,000 crossed into Albania.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration opposes an independent Kosovo.
However, the administration holds Yugoslavia mostly responsibility
for the fighting and bloodshed in the province of southern Serbia.
The ethnic Albanians have been on the offensive lately.
</P>
<P>
The administration wants to nail down the pledges of the rebels
to negotiate before the Contact Group -- Britain, France, Germany,
Russia, the U.S. and Italy, meets in Bonn, Germany, next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke and Gelbard discussed strategy for Kosovo in a video
hookup Tuesday with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
President Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, in a
video hookup, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
