<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Federal Reserve Urges Banks to Maintain Lending Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
Tuesday urged banks to "maintain their lending discipline" after
an intensive study showed a significant relaxation of lending
terms over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Although the country's economy is so good, the central bank
said, most loans haven't gone bad. It cautioned, "This is a
critical time for banks to maintain their lending discipline."
</P>
<P>
"The study identified noteworthy and measurable easing in bank
lending terms," the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
The Fed's concern is that borrowers who have had little trouble
making loan payments during good times, which have lowered the
nation's unemployment rate to a 28-year low, might begin to
struggle if economic growth slows down and unemployment begins to
creep higher.
</P>
<P>
"Banks should resist any tendency to assume in evaluating
credits that the unusually favorable economic environment of the
last few years will continue indefinitely," the Fed said.
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch economist Bruce Steinberg, for instance, is
estimating the economy's seasonally adjusted annual growth rate
has slowed from a torrid 5.4 percent in the first quarter to just
1 percent in the current quarter and will average only 2 percent
in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The lending study was issued as the Fed's monetary
policy-makers are scheduled to have a two-day meeting to determine
the future course of interest rates. It compared several hundred
loans made across the country in late 1995 and late 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The study concludes that intense competition for loan
customers has led to significant easing of pricing and some
nonprice terms," the Fed said in a letter to banks' chief
executive officers.
</P>
<P>
Previous Fed reports showed that banks had tightened up
modestly on consumer lending in the face of individual
bankruptcies soaring past 1 million a year. But the same reports
also indicated a relaxation in business loan terms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980701.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson: U.S. Firing at Iraq's Radar Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. firing at a radar
site in southern Iraq was an appropriate response, Bill
Richardson, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Pentagon said Tuesday that a U.S. F-16 aircraft
fired at the Iraqi radar site after the Iraqi radar locked on to
allied aircraft patrolling a no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Richardson said, "There was a violation
of military protocol. This is simply an appropriate response to a
violation. That is the American position."
</P>
<P>
A no-fly zone in northern Iraq was imposed by the United
States, Britain and France in 1991 after the Gulf War when Baghdad
flew helicopter gunships to quell a Kurdish uprising. Another
no-fly zone was imposed in the south in 1992 to protect Shi-ite
Moslems who also rebelled against Baghdad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
